<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Communications Workshop Opens in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Third African Communications
Regional Workshop aimed at dismystifying communications
technological language and improving satellite and other
frequency-based communication system in the region opened here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the workshop Lemba Nyirenda said in an interview
with reporters that the aim of the workshop was to come up with
resolutions that would help to bridge the gap between technology
designers and the users.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the language used in technology and
communications was too complex for an ordinary person to
understand and efficiently apply it.
</P>
<P>
Nyirenda said the knowledge acquired in universities and
colleges in the fields of communication technology should be
simplified in a way that people with low education could also
understand.
</P>
<P>
He said the participants would come up with ways of translating
 difficult technical language into an easy information package
that could assist the consumers and retailers to use the machines
and other technical tools without a lot of problems.
</P>
<P>
The workshop coordinator, Anthony Ngoma, said earlier that the
event would accrue some economic advantages to the region in
general and Zambia in particular.
</P>
<P>
He said the workshop would focus on the research findings on
the status of weather patterns in the region, which has for some
time been incorrectly deduced.
</P>
<P>
The research has proved that the weather patterns in the
region, specifically that of Zambia, Uganda and Tanzania, which
has been wrongly classified by the International
Telecommunications Union in terms of amount of rainfall received,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator said Zambia would economically benefit from the
 correction in that communication equipment since satellites would
now work more efficiently as they would be made according to the
right weather patterns obtaining in the country.
</P>
<P>
Among the companies represented at the five-day workshop are
Zambia Telecommunications Authority, Telecel, Zamcel and other
telecommunication companies and some government departments.
</P>
</TEXT>
