<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique's National Campaign Against Polio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal
Mocumbi Monday launched a new national campaign against the
childhood disease polio, calling upon the people to participate in
the drive.
</P>
<P>
With the great efforts made by the Mozambican government,
polio cases are rarely reported in the southern African country,
said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi said that as in the previous year, all the 3.3 million
children under the age of five years are expected to be vaccinated
this year.
</P>
<P>
The anti-polio drive will be carried out in two stages: the
first from July 26 to 30, and the second from August 30 to
September 3.
</P>
<P>
During the campaign, some children will also be vaccinated
against measles, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the 41st Congress of the World Health Organization in May
1988, the Mozambican government promised it would wipe out polio
in the country by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The polio cases reported had dropped from 60 in 1980 to four in
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
