<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Readiness of SADC Free Trade Accord Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The South African Chamber of
Business said Monday it would present a memorandum to the
government outlining its concerns on the proposed Southern Africa
Development Community (SADC) free trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
The chamber said its members had for some time expressed "grave
concern" at the desire on the part of the South African government
to ratify and implement the agreement before important
fundamentals are in place.
</P>
<P>
While it recognized and supported the importance of economic
integration for the region, the chamber questioned "the soundness
of ratifying such an agreement in the absence of, inter alia,
customs and effective border control systems which are vital to
contain potential abuse and fraud."
</P>
<P>
It added that many problems were presently being experienced
with cross-border abuses within the Southern African Customs Union
(Sacu) which stemmed from inadequate trans-national mechanisms
with limited powers to deal with abuses.
</P>
<P>
"This serious defect is demonstrated by the apparent inability
of South Africa to upgrade and strengthen its very own border
control systems and to ensure that the present Sacu agreement is
honored," it said.
</P>
<P>
the Sacu groups South Africa, Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho and
Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
Among the areas of concern are: The lack of cooperation and
enforcement of valuation procedures of imports for duty and VAT,
and the shortage of staff and support to handle anti-dumping
issues, as far as SADC applications are concerned.
</P>
<P>
The South African Chamber of Business would like to see a
special court created to handle commercial offenses and the
up-grading of both South Africa's domestic capability and that of
the SADC to police cross-border trade abuses.
</P>
<P>
"Unless our government grasps the seriousness of these
potential negative economic effects, the benefits of an FTA (free
trade agreement) will be dissipated and undermine the already
brittle business fabric in South Africa," said the chamber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
