<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Urges U.N. Meeting on Killing of Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia has demanded
that the U.N. Security Council meet on measures for the protection
of all nationalities in Kosovo, a Serbian province of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY).
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by charge d'affaires of its Permanent
Mission to the United Nations Vladislav Jovanovic in a letter
dated July 24 to the council president, Malaysia's Ambassador Agam
Hasmy.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, distributed as a council document on Monday,
Jovanovic said the killing of 14 Serbs in a village of Kosovo last
Friday is the "most ruthless" in a series of atrocities that the
armed gangs of the so-called Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA)
committed against the non-Albanians recently.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "is duty-bound to take all necessary
measures" to "put an end to the ethnic cleansing of the
non-Albanian population", the Yugoslav diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
"I have been instructed by my Government to request you to
urgently convene a meeting of the Security Council to adopt
necessary measures to ensure the full protection of the Serbian,
Montenegrin, Roma and other non-Albanian populations of Kosovo and
Metohija and the full implementation of Security Council
resolution 1244 (1999) and the military agreement," the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
Attached to the letter is a statement by the Yugoslav
leadership calling for the immediate arrest of criminal groups who
killed the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The U.N., Secretary-General Kofi Annan's Kosovo special
representative Bernard Kouchner issued a statement Saturday on his
behalf saying that he "expects an urgent and relentless
investigation to bring the perpetrators to justice without delay".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
