<HEADLINE> Meeting for DRC Rebels Going on in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The meeting in Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam, which entered
the fifth day on Monday, is aimed at persuading the rebels to
choose a leader to endorse the Lusaka peace accord to end the
11-month-old strife in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's Minister of Foreign Affairs and International
Cooperation Jakaya Kikwete remained mum about the meeting, with a
top official revealing that it is still going on.
</P>
<P>
The official, who declined to be identified, said that the
meeting even prevented the ministry from presenting its budget
estimates before the National Assembly in the central city Dodoma
in time.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministry had planned to table its budget estimates
for the 1999/2000 fiscal year on Tuesday but has been forced to
postpone the date to July 30 to give way to diplomatic efforts to
resolve the conflict in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Officials from Zambia, Rwanda and Uganda are assisting
Tanzanian foreign minister Kikwete, who chairs the closed-door
meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said a joint communique(&AMP; will be made public when the
meeting is over. At present, he said, only the foreign minister
can comment on any progress.
</P>
<P>
Six African governments involved in the war signed a cease-fire
 agreement on July 10 in Zambian capital Lusaka. However, rebels
refused to sign following a leadership wrangle.
</P>
<P>
Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, who is based in the third largest city
of of Kisangani in northeast Congo (K) and represents a faction of
the main rebel Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD), has arrived in
Dar es Salaam for the talks.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Pierre Bemba, leader of the Congolese Liberation Movement
(MLC) who occupies several northern towns, and Emile Ilunga, who
deposed dia Wamba as head of the RCD, have also sent
representatives to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda backs Ilunga, who is based in Goma town in eastern
Congo, while Uganda supports the MLC. Zambia, which has been
leading the mediation efforts, is trying to solve differences
between Ugandan and Rwandan-backed factions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
