<HEADLINE> Egyptian Leader Optimistic for Mideast Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on
Monday said he is encouraged that the Middle East peace process
is moving forward since Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak took
office in early July.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak made the remarks while addressing a joint press
conference with Turkish President Suleyman Demirel after their
meeting in the Mediterranean port city of Alexandria, 220
kilometers northwest of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is time to stop talking about pessimism over
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I am very optimistic" about the Arab-Israeli peace talks,
Mubarak added.
</P>
<P>
Demirel, who visited Israel and the Palestinian self-areas
earlier this month, called the peace process "a golden opportunity
that should not be missed."
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains close ties with Egypt and has a growing
political and military relationship with Israel despite suspicions
among Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Middle East peace talks stagnated under former hard-line
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. There has been renewed
optimism since the election of Barak, who has vowed to push
forward with the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Demirel, who paid a one-day visit to Alexandria, also
discussed with Mubarak ways of promoting bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
After the summit meeting, the two countries signed eight
agreements on cooperation in trade, energy, crime-fighting,
agriculture, health and political consultations.
</P>
<P>
Demirel also visited an Egyptian project to build a world-class
library in Alexandria, once the home to one of the greatest
libraries of the ancient world.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president donated to the project 2,000 books on
subjects ranging from Turkish archaeology to Ottoman and Islamic
history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
