<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Back Home From Tanzania Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
returned home Monday afternoon from a two-day working visit to
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Museveni, together with his host President
Benjamin Mkapa, attended the Heroes' Day ceremonies held in Mleba
district near Uganda border Sunday, a press release from the
President's Office said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the two presidents have probably
discussed the cease-fire agreement signed by the six warring
nations in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The DRC rebels have not signed on the agreement due to a
dispute over which group will sign on the accord on behalf of the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
Uganda, together with Rwanda, has been backing the rebels who
took up arms early last August to oust Congolese President Laurent
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that during the talks, Mkapa has urged Museveni
to persuade the Congolese rebels to ink the pact on the cease-fire
in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
The Heroes' Day ceremonies in Tanzania were carried out in
remembrance of the fallen Tanzanian soldiers who died 20 years ago
during the struggle to eject Ugandan dictator Idi Amin's forces of
occupation out of Tanzanian territories.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni reportedly visited some schools in Tanzania
and donated some money to those schools.
</P>
<P>
He was received at Kololo airstrip by Minister in charge of the
 Presidency Ruhakana Rugunda and other senior Ugandan officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
