<HEADLINE> S. African Rand Ends Weaker Due to Soft Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The South African currency
rand Monday ended weaker against the U.S. dollar as the bond
market drifted softer and the gold price failed to improve from
the 253-dollar-per-ounce level.
</P>
<P>
The rand was last traded at 6.1335 per dollar Monday, compared
with 6. 1025 last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the weaker bond market contributed significantly
to the rand's misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
Yield of the government 150-rand (25-dollar) bond was last seen
at 14.415 percent from 14.100 percent at last Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the weak bond market might lay further pressure on
the rand, but the economic data due this week is expected to offer
support for both the rand and bond markets.
</P>
<P>
Statistics South Africa is due to release the producer
inflation and foreign trade data for June on Wednesday. The
Reserve Bank, central bank of the country, is scheduled to release
the M3 money supply and private sector credit extension data
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
