<HEADLINE> Agro-Industry to Get Boost in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is working
on modalities to decentralize the supply of inputs so as to boost
agriculture in the country, the Zambia Daily Mail newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Lusaka Province Minister Sonny Mulenga as
saying during the opening of the 19th Provincial and Agriculture
Show over the weekend that transport costs would be eliminated if
inputs were taken close to the farmers.
</P>
<P>
Mulenga also encouraged peasants to concentrate on growing
traditional crops to ensure food security.
</P>
<P>
He said small-scale farmers who grow 75 percent of maize in the
country should take agriculture as a business if they are to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need for small-scale farmers to form
cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
Mulenga said very few farmers have taken advantage of the
Cooperatives Act which was introduced in Parliament recently.
</P>
<P>
He further reaffirmed the government's commitment to supporting
small- scale farmers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the show chairman Duncan Chataya disclosed that the
1998/1999 agricultural season is expected to produce close to
100,000 tons of maize.
</P>
<P>
He attributed lower production to the late supply of inputs by
the Food Reserve Agency of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
