<HEADLINE> U.N. Agencies Lack $434 Million for Balkans This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- U.N. humanitarian agencies
on Monday urged donors to continue funding their work in the
countries of south-eastern Europe affected especially by the
Kosovo war, according to a press release issued in New York.
</P>
<P>
The agencies, including U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR), U.N. Development Program (UNDP), U.N. Children's Fund
(UNICEF), U.N. Office for the Coordinations of Humanitarian
Affairs (OCHA) and several others, said over 500 million U.S.
dollars have been raised for the Balkans this year.
</P>
<P>
But some 290 million dollars are needed for the rest of the
year in the aftermath of the Kosovo crisis, in addition to 144
million dollars to fund other relief work for those affected by
earlier Balkan wars such as the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, the former Yugoslav
Republic of Macedonia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY)
are listed as countries affected by the Earlier wars.
</P>
<P>
OCHA/UNHCR said in the press release that a significant portion
of the funds will be devoted to Serbia and Montenegro which have
received 170,000 non-Albanian refugees from Kosovo after the
withdrawal of the Serbian forces from the Serbian province of FRY.
</P>
</TEXT>
