<HEADLINE> Iran Dismisses Turkey's Claim on Presence of PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Iran Monday brushed aside the claim
by Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit on the presence of
Turkish Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) rebels in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Terming Ecevit's remarks as "baseless," Iranian Foreign
Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said the PKK case is a
domestic issue of Turkey, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to stress that attributing domestic problems of
Turkey to the Islamic Republic of Iran would not help good
neighborliness and all-out expansion of relations between the two
neighboring countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said recently that Iran has taken over the role
formerly played by Syria in supporting and harboring the PKK, but
he stressed that Turkey wants to resolve with Iran through
diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
"We never wish that the tension between Turkey and Iran leads
to a heated confrontation," the Turkish Daily News Monday quoted
Ecevit as saying. "But it is a fact that after Syria halted its
support of the PKK to a certain extent, Iran took over Syria's
role."
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels has been fighting a guerrilla war since 1984 for
an independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. The conflicts
between the rebels and government forces have claimed some 37,000
lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
