<HEADLINE> Egyptian Given Jail Term for Abusing Religion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A retired Egyptian civil servant who
claimed to be God's messenger has been convicted of abusing
religion and sentenced to five years in jail, police officials
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The officials said Mohammed Ibrahim Mahfouz was found guilty
Sunday of "spreading radical ideas, sedition, abuse of religion,
and undermining social security."
</P>
<P>
Other thirteen men were also given prison terms, ranging from
one to three years, on charges of collaborating with Mahfouz.
</P>
<P>
Mahfouz, former head of a state shipping firm's board, was
arrested in December last year with a group of followers in the
port city of Alexandria, 220 kilometers northwest of Cairo.
