<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Inflation Rate Worries Zimbabwean C. Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe,
central bank of the country, said Monday that tight monetary
policy to reduce inflation which stands at 55.2 percent must be
supported by a robust fiscal policy as the situation demanded
immediate correction.
</P>
<P>
"To the extent that the government has directed that its
overdraft with the Reserve Bank must be reduced to zero, the
treasury bill rate will be expected to adjust in line with
government funding requirements," the central bank said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
It said the bank rate would be maintained at a level of five
percentage points above the effective treasury bill rate with
immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
The treasury bill rate was determined by market forces in
relationship to the demand for funding by the government and
availability of funds, said the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, price stability continued to be its main objective
and priority, it added.
</P>
<P>
"A major challenge facing the economy, therefore, is high
inflation," it said. "Projections indicate further price increases
by the end of the third quarter." 
</P>
</TEXT>
