<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Stresses Importance of Dialogue With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday stressed the
importance of its present dialogue with neighboring Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that the need for communication between
Greece and Turkey was critical. The talks provided a chance to
examine Turkish intentions, he added.
</P>
<P>
While saying that the procedures getting under way Monday were
difficult and stubborn, he said that Greece must be flexible and
calm.
</P>
<P>
If these talks were successful, then it would be to the
advantage of both sides, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that any negative development that might
rise would be born by Turkey because this time it was Greece which
had chose to move and not third parties.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated that Greece would not to discuss with
Turkey issues concerning the country's sovereign rights.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Parliament President Apostolos Kaklamanis Monday
expressed his displeasure at the recent Turkish provocations in
the Aegean Sea as a Greek-Turkish dialogue was getting under way
in Ankara, Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Dialogue got underway in Ankara Monday between senior foreign
ministry officials of Greece and Turkey in a bid to improve the
strained bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue, which was agreed on early this month between
Greek and Turkish Foreign Ministers George Papandreou and Ismail
Cem, will focus on bilateral cooperation in the fields of
commerce, environmental protection and tourism.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday and Friday, the dialogue will be switched to
Athens, where both sides will discuss cooperation between the two
countries on combating organized crime, illegal immigration,
drugs, terrorism and culture.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have
been strained over decades for their disputes in the territorial
waters, air space limits, the delimitation of the continental
shelf in the Aegean Sea and the Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
