<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARF to Develop Forum Process Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF)
Monday decided to develop the evolving process of the forum at a
"comfortable pace."
</P>
<P>
In the chairman's statement issued at the end of the 6th ARF,
participants at the 6th ARF stressed that the process of the forum
will be developed "at a pace that is comfortable to all
participants."
</P>
<P>
They also reaffirmed their commitment to make decisions by
consensus which they said "has contributed to steady progress
being made."
</P>
<P>
The ARF was attended by foreign ministers from the 22 ARF
members, including the 10 ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian
Nations) member countries, their 10 dialogue partners, Mongolia
and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The ministers emphasized the importance of "confidence
building," the first phase in the ARF's process, to the success of
the ARF and encouraged the further development of confidence
building measures.
</P>
<P>
They decided to discuss the concept and principles of
"preventive diplomacy," the second phase, before they may consider
moving into it from the current first phase.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN will be preparing the draft paper on the concept and
principles of preventive diplomacy for discussion among ARF
members.
</P>
<P>
"The ARF is a framework for political and security dialogue and
cooperation in the region and that its discussions and activities
should be focused on issues which would have significant impact on
regional security," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed that the ARF would maintain its
evolutionary approach as the process progresses from confidence
building to preventive diplomacy and, as an eventual goal, the
elaboration of approaches to conflict resolution.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's 10 dialogue partners includes China, Japan, Russia, the
European Union and the United States, among others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Emergency Food Airlifted to Central Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) Monday airlifted 501 tons of food to the capitals of
the central provinces of Huambo and Bie where the war pit the
Angolan government troops against the UNITA rebels fiercely.
</P>
<P>
Maria Flyn, spokeswoman for WFP office in Luanda, said the
humanitarian situation in the two provincial capitals, Huambo and
Kuito, is "worrisome" and that the WFP is providing assistance "as
more as possible."
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman noted that there are 230,00 and 170,000
refugees in Huambo and Kuito respectively while war-created
refugees are found in all provincial capitals around this southern
African country.
</P>
<P>
In northern city of Malanje where the most fierce fightings are
going on, there are some 100,000 refugees, she said.
</P>
<P>
However, Flyn said that the WFP can only afford to help 500,000
to 600, 000 refugees because it doesn't produce grain and edible
oil and only distributes materials received from international
donors.
</P>
<P>
Just on Sunday, Angolan Minister of Social Assistance and
Resettlement Albino Malungo complained that the funds donated by
the international community "is only a grain of sand in the
desert", noting that the 1.7 million refugees in Angola need some
200 million U.S. dollars in relief.
</P>
<P>
Flyn also announced that the 10,000 tons of maize donated by
the European Union arrived in Angola Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
