<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Existing-Home Sales Surge to New Record in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. sales of existing homes
jumped 10.6 percent in June to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 5.53 million units, the highest level ever, the National
Association of Realtors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The big jump in sales in June followed two consecutive monthly
declines. In May, existing-home sales fell to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 5 million units. And in April, sales
dropped to 5.25 million units after hitting what was then an
all-time high of 5.42 million units in March.
</P>
<P>
June's recorded performance was better than projections by many
analysts, who expected sales of 5.11 million units last month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, mortgage interest rates in June were at the highest
level in two years. According to Freddie Mac, the mortgage
company, the average rate on a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage was
7.55 percent in June, up from 7.15 percent in May, as compared to
7 percent in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Association said that existing home sales were up all parts
of the country last month. But the biggest gains in sales were in
the Northeast, rising 11.1 percent to an annual rate of 700,000
units.
</P>
<P>
The Association's report follows a government report last week
that construction of new homes and apartments fell sharply in June
to the lowest level in just over a year.
</P>
<P>
Economists blamed that performance on rising mortgage rates and
a shortage of skilled workers and some building materials, and
suggested it was a sign that one of the economy's booming sectors
could be cooling off.
</P>
<P>
The Association also said the national median sales price for
existing homes rose 4.3 percent to 137,000 dollars in June over
June 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
