<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd Day of Bangladeshi Opposition Road March Ends Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The second day of Bangladesh's
opposition alliance's road march ended peacefully on Monday amid
fresh calls for mid-term elections, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a series of public meetings on Monday, the second of
the three-day march of the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP), in
northern Bangladesh's Mymensingh and Sherpur districts, BNP
Chairperson and leader of the Opposition in Parliament Khaleda Zia
asked people to prepare to join the next "Dhaka Chalo" (Dhaka
siege) program to force the government to quit from power.
</P>
<P>
This would overthrow the government "through action programs"
including sieges and strikes, she said.
</P>
<P>
Accusing the government of failing to fulfill its pre-election
pledges and increasing the prices of agricultural input such as
fertilizers and seeds, she said the farmers were being deprived of
the just prices of their produce, and their bones had been broken
due to the wrong policy of the government.
</P>
<P>
Former president and chairman of the Jatiya Party (JP) Hussain
Muhammad Ershad also called for a mass movement to unseat the
present government. "There is no alternative to removing the
present government to save the country and free the people," he
told a public meeting in the southern Barisal district on Monday,
the second day of JP's four-day march.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance, comprising the major opposition -- the
BNP, the JP, the Jamaat-e-Islami and the Islami Oikya Jote (IJO),
started on Sunday their second road march this year to different
corners of the country to intensify the anti-government agitation.
</P>
<P>
The program was aimed at protesting what they said the ruling
Awami League's misrule, corruption, repression, subservient
foreign policy and activities against national interests, as well
as the power crisis, deteriorating law and order situation, and
spiraling prices of essentials.
</P>
<P>
The BNP began its march from Dhaka to northern Mymensingh
district, the JP its "launch procession" from the capital to
Barisal, south Bangladesh, the Jamaat its three-day march from
Bogra district, 170 kilometers northwest of here, to the western
district of Chapainawabganj, and IOJ a two-day march from Dhaka to
southeastern Chittagong district.
</P>
<P>
The alliance staged similar road marches in mid-May this year
to whip up a campaign against the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
