<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Territory and Sovereignty Not Allowed to Separate: People's Daily Commentator (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A People's Daily commentary to be
published tomorrow points out that Chinese territory and
sovereignty can not be separated.
</P>
<P>
Lee Teng-hui openly publicized his "Two-States" statement
through the foreign media, the article says, exposing his real
ambition to split Chinese territory and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Widely condemned for his separatist remarks, Lee still goes his
own way trying to split Taiwan from the motherland. Lee's theory
is accepted by some separatists in the island, who attempt to turn
the "Two-States" theory into the policy of Taiwan, and intend to
amend the constitution according to the theory, the article says.
</P>
<P>
Lee has been engaged in promoting Taiwan independence for a
long time, and is deliberately planning to split Taiwan from the
motherland, the article notes.
</P>
<P>
"But it was never before done so openly or boldly. This time
his open remarks that relations between Taiwan and the mainland
should be dealt with on a "State-to-State" basis shed his mask,
exposing his attempt at Taiwan independence," the article says.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, this time Lee again made the mistake of wishful
thinking that the world would go along with his theory and make
Taiwan an international issue, thereby seeking an excuse for
intervention by international forces. Although the world is not
peaceful at present, peace and development are still the general
trend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Bankers Urged to Build Risk Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The National Bank of Ethiopia,
central bank of the country, Monday called on local banks to
develop an effective risk management mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Opening a training program for commercial bankers and bank
supervisors in Addis Ababa, Governor of the central bank Teklewold
Atinafu said that competitive and volatile banking environment
poses great risk to the sector.
</P>
<P>
loans and advances constitute, on average, over 52 percent of
total assets of banks in Ethiopia, Teklewold said, adding that
more than 75 percent of the total income of banks comes from
interest earned on loans and advances.
</P>
<P>
"Loans and advances are the primary sources of bank profits.
At the same time, they can be the single most important causes of
bank failures in this country unless they are properly managed,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The governor said that Ethiopia had introduced far-reaching
changes in the banking sector after it embarked on a comprehensive
economic and structural reform in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Joseph E. Pegues, senior banking sector specialist with the
World Bank, said that lack of transparency, weak credit
management, and unsound supervision were some of the causes of the
recent financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The training is directed to avoid such problems and to create
common framework among bankers in Ethiopia," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian central bank organized the four-day training on
credit risk management in collaboration with the World Bank.
About 25 participants from government and private banks
participated in the training, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
The training aims at identifying and meeting the
capacity-building needs of the financial sector in Ethiopia as
required by the on-going economic reform program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
