<HEADLINE> ASEAN Forum Hopes For Stable Ties Among Major Powers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and the grouping's
dialogue partners Monday expressed the concern that the relations
among the major powers in the Asia-Pacific were affected by events
in other regions, including that in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers, attending a regional security forum in
Singapore, said that stable relations among the major powers were
an integral element underpinning regional stability.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers recognized that the state of relations among the
major powers in the Asia-Pacific was affected by events in other
regions," said the chairman's statement issued at the end of the
6th meeting of the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF).
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the statement said, the foreign ministers
discussed the Kosovo crisis and the developments in Yugoslavia,
and were concerned with the events' wider implications.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the ministers welcomed the regular exchanges
of visits between the major powers, including those at the
leadership level, which have contributed to their stable
relations.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also stressed the importance of the major powers
continuing to promote dialogue and cooperation among themselves
through all available modalities, including the ARF.
</P>
<P>
On NATO's 11-week air strikes against Yugoslavia, the ministers
expressed their deep regret over the loss of thousands of innocent
lives and reaffirmed their support for the U.N. Charter and
respect for the basic principles of international law.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also expressed their deep regret over the U.S.
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia in early May and
extended their sympathy and condolences to the Chinese people and
the relatives of the victims.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's 10 members, the grouping's 10 dialogue partners
including China, Russia, Japan and the United States, and Mongolia
and Papua New Guinea were represented at the one-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
Participants also discussed the security implications of the
regional economic and financial crisis, which had a significant
economic, political and security impact on the region.
</P>
<P>
They said the ARF should continue to pay attention to the
security implications of the crisis. The ASEAN region's economy is
beginning to recover, but continued restructuring and policy
reform would be needed to sustain the recovery, they said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also discussed trans-boundary problems that could
have a significant impact on regional security, the statement
said. The illegal accumulation of small arms and light weapons
have posed a threat to peace and security in many regions and the
international community should focus its attention on this
problem, it said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers voiced concern over the problem of piracy in the
region and said cooperative approaches are needed to deal with it.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Board to Discuss Aid to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Monday said it will hold its board meeting on aid to
Zimbabwe on August 2, 1999.
</P>
<P>
IMF Director for Africa Goodall Gondwe told the Zimbabwe News
Agency Ziana in a telephone interview from Washington that the IMF
staff had proposed that the board give Zimbabwe 200 million U.S.
dollars over the next 14 months.
</P>
<P>
He said, "It was not a board decision but the IMF staff which
made the proposal to the board which will consider this request.
The 212 million U. S. dollars was supposed to be for three years
but this 200 million U.S. dollars is for 14-months."
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Mail reported on July 18 that the IMF had finally
agreed to disburse 200 million U.S. dollars over the next 14
months starting in two weeks' time under a new balance of payments
support agreement.
</P>
<P>
It said all outstanding issues had now been resolved between
the IMF and the Zimbabwean government.
</P>
<P>
Gondwe said, "The biggest thing that has happened is that
Zimbabwe and ourselves have agreed on a program which we are to
take to the board. Zimbabwe and the IMF staff hope this is going
to be approved."
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe would not get the whole amount at once and
expressed the hope that the amount approved would be released
almost immediately after the board meeting.
</P>
<P>
The disbursement of the funds would put an end to an almost
two-year wait by Zimbabwe to receive the much needed balance of
payments support expected to shore up the country's ailing
economy, strengthen the local currency and unlock more than 300
million U.S. dollars support from other international donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
