<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Hong Kong Seek Ways to Promote Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 26 (Xinhua) -- There were great potentials
for Hong Kong and South Africa to increase the two-way trade,
visiting Hong Kong Finance Secretary Donald Tsang said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tsang was speaking after co-chairing a South Africa/ Hong Kong
trade and investment workshop with Trade and Industry Minister
Alec Erwin in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Trade between South Africa and Hong Kong totalled about 1
billion U.S. dollars last year -- less than one percent of Hong
Kong's total foreign trade, according to Tsang.
</P>
<P>
"I think that with an economy like South Africa's, a lot more
is possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Tsang said bilateral investment was
also in its infancy. By early 1997, Hong Kong companies had
injected about 187 million dollars in South Africa, with South
Africa investing about 77 million dollars in Hong Kong by the end
of the same year.
</P>
<P>
"This simply means that there are plenty of opportunities that
have yet to be fully explored and exploited to our mutual
benefit."
</P>
<P>
Tsang, who is leading a business delegation on a 12-day visit
to South Africa, said Hong Kong was an ideal access market to
China.
</P>
<P>
In turn, South Africa was a gateway to Southern Africa with its
market of about 200 million people.
</P>
<P>
Erwin said the two delegations had discussed the effects of the
recent global economic crisis on their respective economies.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda was the negative impact on developing
countries of developed nations attempting to protect their own
industries.
</P>
<P>
"I found it very interesting that Mr Tsang was raising similar
issues," Erwin said.
</P>
<P>
"We share a common approach to the global economy, we are not
seeking to lock ourselves out from it.
</P>
<P>
"We accept these are realities, which properly managed can be
very positive. But within that acceptance, there seems to be room
to explore how adjustments could be made."
</P>
<P>
Tsang said ways should be found for developing and
industrialized nations to pursue their respective goals within the
global economy.
</P>
<P>
Tsang arrived in South Africa on Sunday leading a business
delegation to explore trade and investment opportunities with
their South African counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong mission represented a number of industries,
including gold and silver, textile, clothing, telecommunications,
toys, seafood and exotic meat. A number officials from the Hong
Kong Trade Development Council also formed part of the delegation.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Tsang would hold talks with President Thabo Mbeki
and Finance Minister Trevor Manuel in Pretoria. He would also meet
Foreign Affairs Minister Nkosazana Zuma, and Reserve Bank
officials.
</P>
<P>
Tsang would lead the trade delegation to Durban and Cape Town
before leaving the country on August 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
