<HEADLINE> Russia Says Balkan Crisis Affects Asia-Pacific Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov said Monday that NATO's military action against Yugoslavia
has cast doubt on the recent years' achievements in international
relations and even affected the situation in the Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regional security forum in Singapore, Ivanov said
there is now an attempt to rely on the use of force in
international relations, and he stressed the indispensable role of
the United Nations in finding ways of resolving conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"The use of force by NATO against Yugoslavia -- without the
sanction of the U.N. Security Council -- has questioned all the
positive achievements in international relations during recent
years, giving rise to natural worries of states for their
security," he said.
</P>
<P>
Stability in the Asia-Pacific region has become more fragile
than a year ago, Ivanov said. "The heavy blow of the Balkan crisis
against the established system of maintaining international peace
and security has affected the regional situation, making it less
predictable and stable."
</P>
<P>
The developments in the Balkans showed that international
stability can be plausible only on the basis of multipolarity, he
said. But "we witness the recurrence of the thinking based on the
use of force, an attempt to rely on the law of force in
circumvention of fundamental norms and principles of the
international law."
</P>
<P>
"It is the enhancement of the role of influential international
organizations, first of all the U.N., strict compliance with the
principles of non-interference into internal affairs of states and
solution of the existing problems exclusively by political means,
that is the alternative to such a development," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We remain confident that the U.N. is a unique regulating
mechanism of the entire system of international relations. The
U.N. is indispensable in finding agreed approaches to the
settlement of conflict situations, ensuring progressive
development of state and finding solutions to global problems," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that increasing support has been voiced in the
region to the ideas of building a multipolar world that would
improve the balance in the system of international relations as a
whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
