<HEADLINE> Mbeki Pledges to Help Persuade Congo (K) Rebels to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 26 (Xinhua)-- South African President Thabo
Mbeki Monday pledged to do everything necessary to persuade
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) rebels to sign a cease-fire
agreement aimed at ending the conflict in the vast central African
country.
</P>
<P>
"We will give all the support that is necessary ... to make
sure that they indeed sign the cease-fire," Mbeki told reporters
after meeting visiting Congolese President Laurent Kabila in
Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said it was imperative that the rebels also endorse the
cease- fire agreed to by the other warring parties in Zambian
capital Lusaka on July 10.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said talks with Kabila also touched on the role South
Africa could play in the reconstruction of the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"So we will look at those questions which are wide-ranging,
affecting the infrastructure, central banks, economic recovery,
and support for the rebuilding of the public service," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, for his part, confirmed that his country was hoping
Mbeki could use his influence to achieve a cessation of
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki played a prominent role in talks leading to the July 10
cease-fire pact in the war-torn DRC, where rebels allegedly backed
by Uganda and Rwanda have been fighting for almost a year to oust
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, along with his allies Namibia, Angola and Zimbabwe,
signed the cease-fire agreement, as did Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
But the rebels did not endorse the treaty because of a dispute
over who was entitled to sign for them. Some groups have since
continued their campaign, capturing towns in the northwest and
south of the third largest African country.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, accompanied by a ministerial delegation, arrived at
Waterkloof air base near Pretoria earlier in the day for what he
described as a working visit.
</P>
<P>
Asked after his meeting with Mbeki how far the rebels were from
 endorsing the cease-fire, Kabila said: "I don't know. I hope
they will sign."  
</P>
</TEXT>
