<HEADLINE> Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- About 100,000 public-sector workers staged a
limited "warning strike" Monday to protest against the
government's privatization plan, threatening further actions if
their messages were not received by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Histadrut Labor Federation ordered workers in government
corporations ranging from the Ben-Gurion International Airport to
state telephone company Bezeq to stop work for three hours during
the period between 9:00 to 15:00 (6:00 GMT-12:00 GMT), allowing
them to decide for themselves when to strike.
</P>
<P>
The strike was in solidarity with workers at the state-owned
Mekorot water company, who have been on strike for the past 22
days in a protest over privatization of the
company. (BC-Israel-Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli and Palestinian legislative bodies on
Monday pledged full cooperation in helping move forward the peace
process, which has advanced little since former Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu came to power.
</P>
<P>
"We'll do all we can and take all measures to strengthen the
peace," Israeli Knesset (parliament) Speaker Avraham Burg said at
a news conference with visiting Palestinian Legislative Council
(PLC) Speaker Ahmed Querie (Abu Ala).
</P>
<P>
Abu Ala's visit to the Knesset is the first ever by a senior
Palestinian official. (BC-Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus' government on Monday reiterated that it
maintains a bi-zonal, bi-communal federation as a solution to the
longstanding issue of division of the island.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is also in favor of a federal solution,"
government spokesman Costas Serezis said, adding that regarding
"internal issues, the two communities should enjoy the highest
possible level of autonomy."
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the federal government should have the
necessary power to guarantee the unity of the state.
(BC-Cyprus-Federation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Secretary General of the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Ahmed Abdurahman on Monday welcomed the meeting to be held
in Cairo in early August between PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat and
leaders of the Palestinian opposition factions.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Arafat and leaders of the Damascus-based
opposition factions will focus on the developments on the
political arena and the destiny of the Palestinian people,
Abdurahman said. (BC-Palestine-Meetings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran Monday brushed aside the claim by Turkish Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit on the presence of Turkish Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) rebels in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Terming Ecevit's remarks as "baseless," Iranian Foreign
Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said the PKK case is a
