<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Chamber of Commerce Urges House to Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Chamber of Commerce on
Monday urged the House of Representatives to support normal trade
relations (NTR) with China, a vote it called "the right step for
American business, workers and consumers."
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining open ties to China is critical for Businesses in
every corner of this country," U.S. Chamber of Commerce President
and CEO Thomas, J. Donohue said, noting trade data showing the
country's nearly 200,000 jobs and 18 billion U.S. dollars in
exports depending on trade with China.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980, every U.S. president has supported granting NTR
status to China.
</P>
<P>
Renewal of China's NTR status would allow foreign goods to be
sold in the United States with average tariffs and ensure that
U.S. goods receive the best tariff treatment China offers to
foreign imports, the Chamber said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"As China offers to open its vast markets as part of its bid to
join the World Trade Organization (WTO), U.S. exports are poised
to grow tremendously. A strong House vote on NTR is important to
U.S. negotiators' efforts to secure a WTO deal that will benefit
American business," Donohue said.
</P>
<P>
The Chamber said that it is mounting a vigorous grassroots and
lobbying effort to secure NTR. More than 115 state and local
Chambers of Commerce around the country have joined the U.S.
Chamber-led "Chambers for China Trade," a growing group from
across the United States committed to expansion of U.S. trade with
China.
</P>
<P>
Many of these chambers have visited or written their Members of
Congress, prepared op-eds for their local papers, and reached out
to their smaller member companies to make sure they are aware of
the tremendous stake small business has in China NTR.
</P>
<P>
The Chamber will continue to press for permanent NTR status for
China upon conclusion of a commercially meaningful WTO agreement
with China, Donohue said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce is the World's largest business
federation representing more than three million businesses and
organizations of every size, sector and region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Urged to Maintain Trade Status for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National Association
of Manufacturers (NAM) Monday urged the House of Representatives
to vote to maintain normal trading relations with China by
defeating Tuesday's scheduled resolution of disapproval.
</P>
<P>
"Normal trading relation is not a favor we are doing for China,
it's a favor we are doing for ourselves," said Dianne Sullivan,
NAM director of trade policy.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. economic health and expansion depends upon selling to
markets outside of our own, and China has one-quarter of the
world's population," Sullivan said, adding that "it would be
foolish and more than a little dangerous" for the United States to
simply disengage from the most populous country in the world.
</P>
<P>
Cutting off normal trade relations will only cede China's
market to America's international competitors, Sullivan said, and
hamper critical efforts to get China inside the multilateral
rules-based system of the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
"China's market offers enormous potential for U.S. companies,
translating into high paying, quality jobs, shareholder and
retiree profits and competitiveness here at home," Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
In seven years, China has moved from the tenth to the fourth
largest U.S. trading partner, behind Canada, Japan and Mexico.
U.S. exports to China have increased 252 percent since 1986,
faster than overall average U.S. export growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
