<HEADLINE> Greek, Russian Officials Hold Talks on Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Senior government officials of
Greece and Russia Monday began here their second round of talks on
cooperation in the fields of economy, industry, science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
The Greek delegation was headed by National Economy Minister
Yiannos Papantoniou while the Russian side was led by Deputy Prime
Minister Valentina Matvienko, the semi-official Athens News Agency
(ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Deputy National Economy Minister Rodoula Zisi said
that existing agreements signed by the two countries provided an
important basis for economic cooperation while there were
extensive private investment incentives in both directions and a
system of Greek credit facilities to Russian regions already in
place.
</P>
<P>
She said that there was interest and prospects for bilateral
cooperation in the fields of tourism, construction, banks, and
especially in telecommunications, after the signing of the Black
Sea optical fibre deal recently.
</P>
<P>
She also stressed the need for developing a comprehensive web
of road, air, rail and shipping transport networks to facilitate
trade, and further potential for cooperation in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Matvienko, who was Russia's ambassador to Greece before she
became deputy premier, Monday also met with Greek Defense Minister
Akis Tsohatzopoulos to discuss the program for the Balkan
reconstruction and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Both sides supported the immediate implementation of a
comprehensive program for the reconstruction of the entire region
and hoped that final decisions regarding stabilization would be
adopted in Sarajevo at the weekend. 
</P>
