<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Common Country Assessment Launched in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Ghanaian government and the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) Monday launched a Common
Country Assessment program in Ghana to harmonize support from
Ghana's development partners.
</P>
<P>
The coordinating program of action is also aimed to strengthen
Ghana's long-term development framework, the Ghana News Agency
(GNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
It will review and analyse Ghana's development situation and
identify key issues and causes of development problems. It will
also analyse the needs and priorities, which would define the
purpose and strategy of U.N. system development assistance to
Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Moses Asaga, a Deputy Minister of Finance of Ghana, who chaired
the function, traced the program to a 1997 U.N. reform initiated
by U.N. Secretary- General Kofi Annan and endorsed by the General
Assembly for country level development operations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. initiative - U.N. Development Assistance Framework
(UNDAF) - lays the foundation for cooperation among the U.N.
system, government and other development partners.
</P>
<P>
Moses Mukasa, U.N. resident coordinator, said that the first
country assessment of Ghana, which was conducted in March 1997,
focused on trends and challenges related to social development in
Ghana.
</P>
<P>
The program would achieve deeper knowledge of development
challenges among the partners involved, based on a common analysis
and understanding of the development situation of the country with
a people-centered approach,

said the U.N. official.
</P>
<P>
To ensure and facilitate a broad and human centered country
assessment, Mukasa said the U.N. country team has chosen
sustainable human development as the analytical framework for the
assessment.
</P>
<P>
Ghana's long-term development framework, Vision 2020, has made
it important to forge strong, strategic partnerships not only
among the U.N. system, but foremost with relevant government
entities, civil society, the private sector and other external
development partners.
</P>
<P>
According to a document from the Ghanaian National Development
and Planning Commission, this calls for an increase in external
resources toward poverty reduction at the domestic front and new
development strategies to attract external support.
</P>
<P>
The assessment mission to be completed in November, would
produce a document that assesses the status and trends of human
development, key development problems and underlying causes as
well as progress on follow-ups to international conferences and
conventions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
