<HEADLINE> U.S. to Offer $500 Million for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States announced on
Monday it would offer up to 500 million U.S. dollars in additional
humanitarian aid for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The aid will be announced at an international donors conference
on Wednesday in Brussels, National Security Advisor Samuel Berger
told a seminar at the Council on Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to announce today that at the conference the
United States will be prepared to commit up to 500 million U.S.
dollars for Kosovo, subject to... confirmation that other donors
will do their part," Berger added.
</P>
<P>
"The European Union and its member nations will be principal
contributors for humanitarian aid and for reconstruction in
Kosovo," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The conference was arranged to raise money for immediate
humanitarian needs for the hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians returning to devastated homes and villages.
</P>
<P>
"In the fall, after a more comprehensive damage assessment is
completed, another conference will mobilize aid for long-term
reconstruction," Berger added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Berger admitted that most Serbs have left Kosovo
after NATO took control of Kosovo. However, he said, "We must
work to create an environment where those Serbs who wish to return
and remain can do so in safety." 
</P>
