<HEADLINE> Albania Drafts Plans for Regional Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Albania has drafted plans for
presentation at the Summit of the Stability Pact for Southeastern
Europe to be held on July 30, the Albanian Telegraphic Agency
(ATA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Albania's plans outlined three fundamental issues of the pact
to be launched in Sarajevo, capital of Bosnia-Herzegovina --
democratization, economic cooperation and reconstruction, and
security in Southeastern Europe, according to the ATA.
</P>
<P>
Albania this time highlighted in its plans the role of economic
cooperation for stability in the region, proposing some priority
cooperation projects for that purpose, especially in the fields of
energy and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Under the plans, the Albanian government will present at the
summit some regional cooperation projects on energy and
infrastructure, including construction of hydro-power stations on
regional rivers and connection of Albania's gas pipeline network
through Italy and Greece to North Africa.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal Milo
Sunday presented the Corridor 8 project in Sofia, capital of
Bulgaria, where he was meeting with his Macedonian counterpart,
Alexksander Dimitrov, and Bulgarian counterpart, Nadezhda
Mihajillova, to coordinate their joint projects for presentation
in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
The Corridor 8 project is designed to link the road network
from the Albanian port of Durres to Macedonia's capital of Skopje,
Sofia and Bulgaria's coastal city of Varna.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton Saturday sent a letter to Albanian
President Rexhep Mejdani, urging Albania to prepare plans for
presentation at the Sarajevo summit.
</P>
<P>
The ATA Monday said that Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko
had urged his ministers to work hard so that the Albanian
government can present a clear and detailed strategy at the
summit.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the summit will take place on July 30 with
the presence of over 50 heads of state and government. 
</P>
