<HEADLINE> Course on plant tissue culture opens in Accra, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Ghana
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Professor J.K.A Amuzu, Pro-Vice
Chancellor of the University of Ghana, Monday urged biologists
to use plant tissue culture principles for the rapid
multiplication of disease-free plants.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Amuzu said modern biology has taken a new turn in
biotechnology and that its principles could also be used for
conservation, the Ghana News Agency (GNA) reported from Accra,
capital of Ghana.
</P>
<P>
He was opening the second international training course in
plant tissue culture, where participants will learn to produce
disease-free plants.
</P>
<P>
It is organized by the Department of Botany, University of
Ghana and the United Nations University/Institute for Natural
Resources in Africa (UNU/ INRA).
</P>
<P>
 The nine participants are from six African Universities --
Ghana, Togo, Nigeria, Benin, Cote d'Ivoire and Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
 They will be taught how to identify plant cells, eliminate
their viruses and use them to produce healthy plants.
</P>
<P>
 Prof. Amuzu said, "our forests are being depleted of useful
medicinal plants, non-timber products and many plants are now on
the list of endangered species awaiting conservation through
tissue culture techniques."
</P>
<P>
 He said the problem is accentuated by the yearly occurrence
of devastating bush fires that take away a heavy toll of many rare
plant species.
</P>
<P>
 "Should we not begin to conserve these vital biological
diversity by applying tools that science can offer," he asked and
appealed to friends of the university and other agencies
interested in the development of science to come to the aid of the
university to organize such programs.
</P>
<P>
 Prof. Uzo Mkwunye, Director of UNU/INRA, said the UNU
agreed to provide 40,000 dollars to the University for expansion
of the existing physical facility of plant tissue culture
laboratory of the Department of Botany.
</P>
<P>
 A similar course was held last year to rethink the vision of
UNU in Africa.
</P>
<P>
 "Today our vision is firmly fixed on the notion that forming
strategic partnerships with the scientists and academics in
Africa's universities and research institutions is the most
appropriate way to promote institutional and human capacity
building in Africa."
</P>
<P>
 He asked the botany department to work closely with INRA to
develop research and training programs and jointly look for
financial resources to support their activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
