<HEADLINE> Murder of Spouses, Problem in Tanzania: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official
of Tanzania said Monday that the murder of spouses remains a
problem in this east African country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a parliament session in the central city Dodoma,
Deputy Minister of Labor and Youth Development William Lukuvi said
that 384 women were killed by their husbands from 1995 to last
May.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, some 144 men were beaten to death by
their wives because of excessive drinking, extra-marital affairs
or other reasons.
</P>
<P>
Lukuvi, who stood in the place of the Minister of Home Affairs,
was answering questions from Monica Mdogo, a parliament member,
who sought to know the number of murder cases related to discord
of spouses and penalties on convicts.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said 94 accused persons, including 61
husbands and 33 wives, were convicted of murder charges between
1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Lukuvi said the remaining cases are still under investigation
and some files have been handed over to the Director of Public
Prosecution, according to reports from Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
He said these are only the officially reported incidents and in
some cases the accused persons have committed suicide or escaped.
</P>
</TEXT>
