<HEADLINE> Kenya's New Civil Services Head Urges to Wipe out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Newly appointed Head of
Civil Service Richard Leakey said Monday that he is confident of
wiping out corruption and inefficiency in government in the
country.
</P>
<P>
While making the remarks at his first news conference here,
Leakey said that he has full support of the president, emphasizing
that corruption would no longer be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
Leakey, appointed as Head of Civil Service and Secretary to the
Cabinet by President Daniel arap Moi last Friday, pointed out that
"public officers who let us down are not going to be transferred
to another place to let us down, but will be removed."
</P>
<P>
Leakey, a white Kenyan, is a famed conservationist in the
country. He was the Director of the Kenya Wildlife Service before
his new appointment.
</P>
<P>
He told the press that "there is a fairly huge task ahead of us
if we are going to restore confidence in the public service."
</P>
<P>
It is learnt that he had given a mandate by the president "to
change the culture of corruption and inefficiency in our public
service."
</P>
<P>
The mandate will be supported by foreign donors and investors
at a time when they are gradually pulling out of the country or
withdrawing development projects due to the rampant corruption in
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Leakey said President Moi had been unequivocal in delivering a
message of transparency and accountability to senior civil service
officials earlier Monday, saying that he had confidence the
president was backing him all the way. 
</P>
