<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Set New Summer Speed Limit to Avoid Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- German drivers will have to comply
with the new summer speed limit by the Environment Ministry next
year, which says the current regulations are insufficient to
prevent severe air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Environment Minister Juergen Trittin told the Suedduetsche
Zeitung newspaper Monday that cars would not be allowed to run
over 100 kilometers per hour on German highways in summer starting
in the year 2000, and the speed limit for trucks would be 60. The
current speed limits are 130 kilometers per hour for cars and 100
for trucks on highways.
</P>
<P>
Martin Waldhausen, a spokesman for the ministry, said in Berlin
that the government found it ineffective only to prohibit cars and
trucks without a catalysator running on German roads to reduce air
pollution in summer days.
</P>
<P>
Under the law valid since 1995, automobiles must be equipped
with catalysator, a reactor made up of platinum to reduce the
emissions, before they can run on German roads. The law does not
stipulate any speed limit for vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The law, drafted by the conservative cabinet under Helmut Kohl,
was aimed at cutting the near-ground smog and ozone pollution by
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
But, under a new European Union law, the ozone level in the air
must be kept under 180 micrograms per cubic meter. The ozone is
the main ingredient that may hurt human health in the smog, the
air pollutant caused by automotive emissions.
</P>
<P>
According to tests in several German states, ozone
concentration is far over 200 micrograms per cubic meter air
without a specific speed limit under high temperature in summer
days. And German environmentalists demand more regulations to
limit the air pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Germany's federal environment bureau supported Trittin's
initiative, saying a more extensive speed limit is needed to cut
the smog pollution.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has calculated that restricting the automotive speed
to 80 percent of the current standards will reduce the ozone
pollution by 5 percent, said Karsten Klenner, a spokesman for the
bureau. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes Global Debt Relief Program to Be Fixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration on
Monday urged international financial leaders to agree in September
on a program to provide debt relief to the world's poorest
nations.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to a development conference at the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said
the world's wealthiest nations had to find "an appropriate way to
finance this relief that would win broad international support."
</P>
<P>
Last month in Cologne, Germany, leaders from the world's seven
largest industrial countries unveiled an initiative to help ease
the crushing debt burdens of the world's poorest countries, most
of them in sub-Sahara Africa.
</P>
<P>
"What is important now is that we take the extra momentum that
the Cologne commitments afford -- to strengthen and accelerate
these efforts and integrate them into a single package by the
fall," Summers said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the international community ought to reach
agreement on such a program at the annual meetings" of the
182-nation IMF and its sister organization, the World Bank, at the
end of September.
</P>
<P>
There is a "historic opportunity to accelerate (debt relief)
efforts and help these countries finally build an attractive
environment for private investment and market-led growth," Summers
said. "We should not and must not allow that opportunity to go to
waste."
</P>
<P>
He said the question of financing the 27-billion-U.S.-dollar
debt relief program "raises some difficult issues." He referred to
a proposal for the IMF to sell 310 metric tons of gold, about 10
percent of its total reserves, which running into mounting
opposition in U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
"Nonetheless, I am confident that working together, we can find
a way to do this in a way that can command broad support," Summers
said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Summers said the Clinton administration was looking
at alternatives to financing debt relief for 41 heavily indebted
poor countries after several key members of both the Senate and
House said sale of IMF reserves could weaken already depressed
gold prices and hurt countries in Africa that rely on gold mining
for export revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
