<HEADLINE> China: Aid Disparity, Unfair to African Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- China Monday criticized
certain donor countries for "selectively and conditionally"
providing aid to refugees.
</P>
<P>
The practice was extremely unfair to African refugees, said Qin
Huasun, representative of China's Permanent Mission to the United
Nations, at a U.N. Security Council meeting on humanitarian
assistance to the refugees in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Fairness and impartiality in humanitarian affairs should be
observed by the international community," he said.
</P>
<P>
While each refugee in Kosovo received 1.60 U.S. dollars per
day, each African refugee only received 0.11 dollars per day, he
pointed to the fact which drew international attention.
</P>
<P>
Qin said Africa had over 3 million refugees and over 2 million
displaced persons, one third of all such people in the world, and
the key to resolving the problem was to remove the root causes.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, he said, the relatively backward economies of
underdeveloped countries, coupled with threats presented by
globalization, threatened many of those countries with
marginalization.
</P>
<P>
Such factors, he said, contributed to the growth in conflict,
poverty and instability and prevented the removal of root causes.
</P>
<P>
As a developing country, Qin said, China had provided
assistance to many African countries through bilateral agreements
and enjoyed a good relationship with the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
