<HEADLINE> European Bourses Slide As Dollar Suffers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON July 26 (Xinhua) - European markets all closed sharply
lower in volatile trading Monday as the dollar remained on the
defensive after being hit by strength in the euro and the yen.
</P>
<P>
The UK's FTSE 100 closed down 38 points, or 0.62 percent, at
6169.1. The index was flat for much of the morning in light trade,
then dramatically slumped more than 110 points to hit a four-month
low of 6092.1 before recovering at the close.
</P>
<P>
Heavyweight oil stocks led the FTSE's fall - BP Amoco lost 1.1
percent and Shell Transport fell 2.55 percent. Pharmaceutical
shares were also pulled back, with SmithKline Beecham off 1.15
percent.
</P>
<P>
Traders said they were expecting the UK market to go higher on
the back of the banking sector's results, but even at its low, the
market never felt like it was down 115 points.
</P>
<P>
Germany's DAX index fell about 2 percent on the day as strength
in the euro combined with a lower start on Wall Street to extend a
correction after the market's climb to fresh year highs earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
The DAX ended down 104.1 points, or 1.96 percent, at 5206.44.
"The stronger euro, the weaker dollar, a lower start on Wall
Street - it's all added up," one trader said.
</P>
<P>
Paris CAC-40 closed down 1 percent at 4395.91 in volume of 2.1
billion euros, but off the day's low of 4360.77 as the Dow's early
fall was less severe than had been expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
