<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government Report Sums Up Progress, Setbacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
has admitted his government still has much to do to fulfill some
of the Labor Party's election promises made two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Promoting the government's annual report, Blair said Monday
that health and education still required significant changes to
meet his election pledges.
</P>
<P>
The report, published Monday, painted a glowing picture overall
of the administration that produced it, but the opposition
dismissed it as a "gimmick."
</P>
<P>
The report claimed 90 of the party's 177 manifesto commitments
had been met and said another 85 were under way. Only two still
had to be put into the parliamentary timetable, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But the prime minister expressed irritation with delays in
reforms to the health service as he answered questions in an east
London hospital Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
"No one is more frustrated than me, but I think to turn around
a big public service is a 10-year project and it will take time to
do it," he said. "There are still things where we have got to
improve things and do better."
</P>
<P>
In his introduction to the report, Blair said his five basic
pledges were all on course to be met.
</P>
<P>
"In some areas, the government has made good progress but in
other important fields, it will take more time to achieve our
goals," he said.
</P>
<P>
Striking an optimistic note, he said he believed Britain's
influence in the world was growing and that the country was "on
the right track."
</P>
<P>
"Our public services are steadily improving. Working people
have more support, decent standards, paid holiday and more
childcare," he said. "The economy has avoided lurching from boom
to bust."
</P>
<P>
He said one of the government's biggest achievements was that
the nation was starting to look like "a society coming together,
not torn apart." Other success stories cited are falling
unemployment and devolved government in Scotland and Wales.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, the prime minister said it would take years of
hard work before the NHS reforms were in place. But he said the
extra 21 billion pounds, which had been earmarked for health over
three years, was "well under way."
</P>
<P>
Blair also admitted "reforming the complicated web of social
security benefits will take more time before its real impact will
be felt."
</P>
<P>
But before the report was published, it was dismissed by the
Conservative Party as a publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
Shadow Cabinet Office minister Andrew Lansley said, "The point
has come where Labor can no longer publish hyped-up over-stylized
material."
</P>
<P>
"The public's experience is that Labor is letting them down.
Labor's year of delivery so far has been a failure," he said.
"This annual report is necessarily understated for one simple
reason -- because Labor are under-performing."
</P>
<P>
The Conservatives have produced their own version of the
document, entitled Labor's Real Annual Report. In it, they accused
Blair of "fudge, failure or delay" on most of his pledges, a BBC
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
