<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Dips In July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Consumer Confidence
Index dipped nearly three-and-a-half points in July, the first
time after eight months of consecutive gains, the Conference
Board, a prominent research group, said in a report on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Consumer Confidence Index declined 3.4
point to 135.6 in July from 139.0 in June.
</P>
<P>
"Consumers appear to have taken a brief vacation to reflect
on the healthy economy their spending has created, " said Lynn
Franco, Associate Director of the Conference Board's Consumer
Research Center.
</P>
<P>
Franco said, "While the current dip in confidence may
reflect concerns about future job prospects, some tightening
in the availability of credit and the recent interest rate hike,
it does not suggest a long-term erosion in consumer optimism."
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve raised interest rates by 0.25 percent on
June 30 in a "pre-emptive" action to curb inflation. Last
Thursday, the Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan raised the
possibility of the second interest rates hike in a testimony at
the House Banking Committee and the remarks have dragged the
stock market lower.
</P>
<P>
The report said consumers' outlook six months form now was
much less optimistic than in the previous survey. The
percentage of respondents anticipating a pickup in business
conditions dropped to 16.4 percent form 18.1 percent in June and
those expecting conditions to worsen, however, only increase
moderately from 5.6 percent last month to 6.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
