<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Announce Amnesty to Free 90,000 Inmates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Justice intends to
announce another amnesty that will free about 90,000 inmates from
its crowded prisons, Russian Justice Minister Pavel
Krasheninnikov said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A group has already been set up to draft the amnesty program,
and appropriate documents will be ready by the end of the year,
the Interfax news agency quoted Krasheninnikov as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that the pardon will cover convicts who pose no danger
to society, such as offenders whose negligence led to road or
traffic accidents and disabled persons, war veterans, minors, and
women who have behaved well and whose prison term is under five
years.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that overall, the ministry is planning to
reduce the prison population by 200,000-300,000 in one year to one
and a half year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the current size of the prison population, at one
million, is very high. The over-crowdedness has been blamed for
alarmingly high incidence of such contagious diseases as AIDS and
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
"It is our task to increase the number of prisons and
detention centers while reducing the number of convicts in order
to create decent living conditions for them," Krasheninnikov said.
</P>
<P>
"When we sentence criminals to imprisonment we should not be
sentencing them to be infected with AIDS, TB or other deadly
diseases," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian parliament last month passed an amnesty measure
that calls for the release of 100,000 inmates who are first-time
offenders convicted of lesser crimes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
