<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Russian Policy Blamed for Failure to Stem NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A former Russian ranking
intelligence officer said Tuesday that NATO's eastward expansion
could have been prevented if the country had pursued a single and
coordinated policy.
</P>
<P>
Fyodor Ladygin, former chief of the Russian General Staff's
Main Intelligence Department, told the Nezavisimaya Gazeta
newspaper that NATO enlargement could have been stopped way back
in 1994-1995, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"I think that our amorphous foreign policy, pursued, among
others, by ex-foreign minister Andrei Kozyrev, gave a go-ahead to
the expansion of the alliance," Ladygin said.
</P>
<P>
He said both military intelligence and "other services dealing
with similar tasks were issuing warnings about NATO's enlargement
plans."
</P>
<P>
He said NATO's enlargement eastwards might move the alliance's
strike aviation bases directly toward Russia's borders.
</P>
<P>
"We shall find ourselves under the sword of Damocles - the
danger of a sudden conventional strike. The entire territory of
Russia's European part will be in a zone reachable by NATO
tactical aircraft and cruise missiles," Ladygin warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
