<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 9 Killed in Communal Clash in Ambon, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Nine people have been killed and
32 others injured in communal clash between residents from three
villages outside Ambon, capital of Indonesia's Maluku province,
since Saturday, the Antara News Agency said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The communal clash had spread to downtown Ambon Tuesday, said
the agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted witness reports as saying that Tuesday's
clash started at 06:00 a.m. local time outside Ambon, but later
also involved people living in downtown Ambon. In the town, the
rioters pelted and burnt shops on A.Y. Patty street, which leads
to the town's center.
</P>
<P>
By Tuesday noon, thousands of people were still out in some of
Ambon's main streets carrying sharp weapons. The situation became
more tense after hand-made bombs exploded and shops along three
streets were set on fire.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that some 60 shops had been torched.
</P>
<P>
Maluku police chief Col. Bugis M. Saman personally led police
troops in the streets to calm the crowds, Antara reported.
</P>
<P>
In Jakarta, Indonesian Defense Forces (TNI) spokesman Maj. Gen.
Syamsul Maarif told reporters that TNI Commander Gen. Wiranto had
instructed the military and police chiefs in Ambon to take
whatever measures necessary to prevent the unrest in their region
from escalating or spreading.
</P>
<P>
Located about 2,300 kilometers east of Jakarta, Ambon has been
rocked by religious unrest that has killed more than 200 people
this year.
</P>
<P>
In Ambon, about 60 percent of the population are Christian,
while most of the rest are Muslims, many of them immigrants from
other islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
