still suffering from physical or psychological wounds.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies said in
a news release reaching here Tuesday that "many Kenyans still reel
from the consequences of the explosion as penniless widows
struggle to feed and raise young families, the blind and maimed
face insecure future."
</P>
<P>
A terrorist bomb meant for the U.S. embassy on August 7 last
year tore apart Nairobi's downtown business district, killing
more than 200 people and injuring over 5,000.
</P>
<P>
"The wounds that are left by such a terrorist attack do not
heal overnight," said Al Panico, head of the federation's Nairobi
 regional delegation.
</P>
<P>
"It is a long and agonizing process and the poverty in Kenya
exacerbates the suffering of the bombing victims," Panico added.
</P>
<P>
A Kenya Red Cross program has been offering social and medical
 assistance to the bombing victims. It provides counselling for
the traumatized, surgery and medical care, support for the blind
and disabled and a three-year school fees programs for children
who lost parents and whose education is threatened.  
