<HEADLINE> Arctic Expedition Offers New Insight into Climate Abnormalities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, July 27 (Xinhua)-- China's Arctic expedition
team will solve some of the mysteries surrounding the water
exchange between the Pacific Ocean and the Arctic Ocean through
the Bering Straits, thus contributing to the study of global
climate changes.
</P>
<P>
Scientists with the expedition has concluded its research at 14
sites in the Chukchi Sea, and reached the halfway mark in its
research at the Bering Sea today.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Jinping, an assistant to chief scientist, said, "Climate
change is a global problem, so we can't discover its principles by
studying the phenomenon in China only."
</P>
<P>
Water exchange between the Arctic Ocean and the Pacific Ocean
through the Bering Straits has a great impact on the climate
changes of China, however. The devastating floods last year and
the rainy season in South China has a direct connection with the
ocean, he said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Chinese scientists had accumulated some "
exciting" data from their research in the Bering and Chukchi seas,
which will greatly contribute to research on the water exchange
between the Pacific Ocean and the Arctic Ocean, and to the
forecasting of natural disasters in China.
</P>
<P>
Because of the hazardous ice conditions, Chinese scientists
have been held back from pushing further north, and the expedition
will put off the research in the permanently frozen area, and
carry out further research at the heart of the Chukchi Sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
