<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Health Officials to Discuss Blood Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Australia's state health
ministers will meet next week to discuss blood testing after a
girl in Melbourne city became the first Australian in 14 years to
acquire HIV from donated blood.
</P>
<P>
The girl, whose identity and age have not been released, was
confirmed HIV-positive last Tuesday after undergoing surgery at
Melbourne's Royal Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for federal Health Minister Michael Wooldridge said
blood screening was already on the agenda for next Wednesday's
meeting in Canberra before the Melbourne case emerged.
</P>
<P>
Health ministers are expected to consider the introduction of a
new test for donated blood to show up antibodies that are
undetectable by the tests now in use.
</P>
<P>
Wooldridge, who is overseas, was distressed and concerned about
the situation for the Melbourne girl and her family, his spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
It was the first-known case of HIV transmission since screening
all blood donations for the virus started in May 1985.
</P>
<P>
The case in Melbourne follows a HIV contamination scare at
Canberra Hospital late last year when there were fears for more
than 250 women who may have come in contact with an infected
health worker.
</P>
<P>
Women who had surgery or gave birth at the hospital were
checked for HIV and Hepatitis B but all tests proved negative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
