on ways to boost bilateral ties in all fields as well as Arab and
international issues of mutual concern, according to a statement
issued by Kuwaiti Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Both sides asserted, during the meeting, their keenness to
unify the Arab stand and work toward constructive Arab relations
based on the principles of respecting each country's sovereignty,
non-interference in its internal affairs and peacefully solving
inter-Arab disputes, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also underlined the importance of Iraq's
implementation of all United Nations Security Council resolutions
concerning Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese foreign minister arrived here late Sunday for a
three-day visit primarily aimed at restoring the Sudanese-Kuwaiti
ties.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait downgraded its diplomatic ties with several fellow Arab
nations, including Sudan, which it accused of sympathizing with
Iraq during Baghdad's 1990-1991 seven-month occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Mustafa hoisted his country's flag on the Sudanese
Embassy in Kuwait. He said that raising the flag indicates the
restoration of the brotherly relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He stressed his country "gives the relations full concern and
is keen on maintaining the bridge of friendship between both
nations."
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Kuwait's Minister of Commerce and
Industry and Minister of Social Affairs and Labor Abdul Wahab
Al-Wazzan, the Sudanese minister also hoped for stronger economic
links between the two states, and asked for Kuwait's role in
achieving peace in south Sudan and in Sudan's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The famines and the 16-year-old civil war between Sudanese
government and the south rebels have claimed 1.5 million lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Growth Fast in Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Internet growth is accelerating
faster in developing countries than anywhere else, a report
presented to the Third African Communications Regional Workshop in
Lusaka said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report presented by Zambia Telecommunication corporation
Limited said that Internet users in Africa have passed the one
million mark but South Africa accounts for more than 90 percent of
Internet growth.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, sub-Saharan Africa with a population of 520 million
has fewer than 9,000 Internet hosts whilst North Africa with 130
million inhabitants has only 2,550 hosts, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that all African countries have some form of
Internet access. However, estimates of Internet growth in Africa
need to be treated with caution. Much of the growth occurred in
one country - South Africa. For example, out of the 155,623
hosts, 144,445 are in South Africa which ranks about 16th in world
terms in number of Internet hosts.
</P>
<P>
The poor state of telecommunications infrastructure adversely
affects the Internet, which totally depends on some minimum level
of telecommunications infrastructure for existence, the report
said, adding that measure of tele-density (number of telephone
lines per 100 people) in Africa is the largest constraint.
</P>
<P>
Average tele-density for the developing world is just 1.5,
while in some African countries like Guinea, Liberia, Niger and
Somalia the figure plummets to just 0.002. In Chad and the
Democratic Republic of Congo the figure is 0.0001, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Internet will continue to be one of the buzz-words in the
telecommunications industry, appealing to both operating and new
entrants in the field, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
