<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Urges Reconsideration of Marcos Assets Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government urged
Tuesday the country's graft court, Sandiganbayan, to reconsider
its decision striking down the proposed 150-million-U.S.-dollar
settlement in favor of the human rights victims of the late
president Ferdinand Marcos.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican said the government will
file a motion for the Sandiganbayan to reconsider its decision
made earlier Tuesday which announced the transfer of 150 million
dollars of Marcos assets to about 10,000 human right victims
"illegal and void."
</P>
<P>
According to Barican, the motion will be filed by the Office of
the Solicitor General (OSG) on behalf of the government.
</P>
<P>
The government had asked the Sandiganbayan to approve the
transfer of 150 million dollars of the 590 million dollars of the
Marcos assets now in escrow after it had been transferred from the
Union Bank of Switzerland (UBS) to the Philippine National Bank
(PNB).
</P>
<P>
Asserting the legality of the transfer, Barican said "the OSG
noted that the Swiss Magistrate, Dieter Jann, in a letter to the
Presidential Commission on Good Government (PCGG), expressed no
objection or opposition to the release of the funds to the human
rights victims."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, said Barican, the proposed settlement in favor of the
human rights victims will not violate the law of Comprehensive
Agrarian Reform Program (CARP) which only refers to assets of the
Marcoses that are "in legal possession of the government."
</P>
<P>
Barican explained that "In the present case, the ownership of
the 590-million-dollar fund is still being disputed. Neither is
this fund in the government's possession as contemplated under the
CARP law."
</P>
<P>
According to the CARP law, all proceeds from Marcos-related
sequestered assets shall go to the government's CARP fund to
benefit more farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Parliament Approves Consumer Protection Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian Parliament
approved Tuesday the Consumer Protection Bill 1999 which, among
others, provides for the establishment of a Consumer Claims
Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal will enable consumers to seek compensation for
goods sold if retailers failed to make good on guarantees
including concerning repairs, replacements and refunds.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, traders also face a fine of up to 500,000
ringgit (about 131,578 U.S. dollars) if found guilty of actions to
mislead, making wrong representations and offering goods or
services that are detrimental to the health of consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
