<HEADLINE> EU to Add 35 Million Euro to Its 1999 Kosovo Aid Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- An European Commission spokesman
said Tuesday that the European Union will add another 35 million
euro (36.75 million U.S. dollars) this year to its aid program for
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The offer will be made Wednesday at an international donors
conference in Brussels, Belgium, jointly hosted by the commission
and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the new EU offer would concentrate on
the reconstruction in Kosovo on building houses, restoring
electricity and water supplies, restoring customs service and
supporting local job creation.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Wednesday's conference would hear from
the assessment task force of EU that went to assess the damage
inflicted by the 11-week NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
EU officials so far have estimated that around 120,000 houses
in Kosovo were either completely or partly damaged that need to be
built or re-built before the coming winter.
</P>
<P>
Officials from more than 100 donor countries and international
organizations will attend the one-day conference to discuss urgent
financing requirements, presenting humanitarian aid programs, and
detailing an overall orientation report for a reconstruction
development program to be presented to a further donor pledging
conference slated for October.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, humanitarian assistance provided for Kosovo and
the surrounding region through the EU humanitarian branch ECHO has
amounted to 378 million euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
