<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Stresses Free Movement of Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The free movement of residents of
European Union (EU) member states was once more stressed as the
executive body of the 15-nation union clarified the rights of
residents on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission made the clarification after an
increasing number of complaints from citizens concerning residence
and free movement problem was registered.
</P>
<P>
The complaints focused on member state restrictions on citizens
' fundamental rights of residence and free movement within the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
The commission reiterated the issue in the hope of improving
the implementation of citizens' rights by reducing differences
between member states' interpretation of the rules and by raising
citizens' awareness of their rights.
</P>
<P>
The European Community Treaty entitles member states to
restrict these rights on grounds of public policy, public security
or public health but member states are obliged to ensure that
citizens are offered certain safeguards and guarantees for their
rights.
</P>
<P>
Member states may only take measures to restrict or deny entry
into the country, issue or renew residence permits or expel a
foreign resident on the basis of the personal conduct of the
individual concerned.
</P>
<P>
Previous criminal convictions cannot in themselves constitute
grounds for taking such measures, the commission emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The European Court of Justice said that member states should be
able to demonstrate that an individual represents a "genuine and
sufficiently serious threat" affecting one of the fundamental
interests of society in order to justify a restriction on his or
her right of residence or free movement.
</P>
<P>
A measure cannot remain in force forever and citizens have a
right to re-examination of their case after a reasonable period of
time has elapsed, said the commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Agency Concerned Over Humanitarian Crisis in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The regional office of the United
Nations World Food Program (WFP) expressed here Tuesday its fears
over a worsening humanitarian crisis in southern Sudan as a flight
ban by the government of Sudan across the Western Upper Nile
region enters its second week.
</P>
<P>
The ban, which was announced on July 14, makes most of the
region inaccessible for the WFP and other relief agencies trying
to deliver urgent humanitarian assistance to 150,000 people in an
area continually wrecked by war and insecurity.
</P>
<P>
"We are extremely worried that unless the ban is lifted soon,
we could be heading toward a humanitarian catastrophe, not unlike
the famine last year," said Ramiro Lopes Da Silva, WFP director of
transport and logistics, in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Some people in the region started fleeing their homes just
after the flight ban, said Silva.
</P>
<P>
Between February and April last year, a flight ban imposed by
the Sudanese government meant that little relief assistance could
reach the war- torn region of Bahr El Ghazal, quickly turning a
region into a famine zone.
</P>
<P>
With the announcement of the current ban, which covers five
main population and relief centers in Western Upper Nile, a WFP
team was forced to abandon food distributions in two relief
centers.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the year, WFP has had very limited
access to the Western Upper Nile region, often distributing food
on a "hit and run" basis, where WFP teams stay on the ground just
long enough to receive airdrops and hand out the food.
</P>
<P>
Flight approvals by the Khartoum government are normally issued
at the beginning of each month. The current flight denial to
Western Upper Nile was suddenly imposed in the middle of this
month.
</P>
<P>
WFP is the United Nations' front-line agency in the fight
against global hunger. Last year, its relief workers fed 75
million people, including most of the world's refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's BBA China Factory Starts Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a factory for the
production of adhesive-bonded cloth in north China's Tianjin
Economic and Technological Development Zone began today. The
project is funded by the BBA Industrial Group of Britain, famous
around the world for its aviation industry and materials
technology.
</P>
<P>
The first stage of the project occupies an area of 70,000
square meters, with a total investment of 68 million U.S. dollars.
The entire project is scheduled to be completed in April 2001, and
the factory's annual output is set at 16,500 tons.
</P>
<P>
The decision to establish this factory in Tianjin was made
according to a marketing survey, which showed that China is a
great potential consumer of sanitary products, especially those
for babies and women.
</P>
<P>
However, this aspect is only part of the BBA's business
exploration in China. The company also plans to invest 250 million
dollars to set up an industrial park in the zone, thereby turning
Tianjin into its production base in the Asia-Pacific Region.
</P>
<P>
The multinational BBA is one of the 250 largest British-listed
companies, and its adhesive-cloth division is the third-largest
producer in the world, with nine production bases in six countries
and annual profits of 650 million dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
