<HEADLINE> Chinese Prosecutors Recover 106 Million U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Prosecutors across China recovered
880 million yuan (106.41 million US dollars) of potential direct
economic losses for the state through their investigations of
cases of official corruption in the first half of 1999, said Han
Zhubin, procurator-general of the Supreme People's Procuratorate,
at a national tele-conference here today.
</P>
<P>
In the January-June period, procuratorates at all levels
handled 52,041 complaints of official corruption or dereliction of
duty, conducted preliminary checks into 39,684 cases, and filed 18,
192 for criminal investigation, Han told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Prominent cases brought to the court by prosecutors include a
number of felonies perpetrated by high-ranking officials and law-
enforcement officials, both in the judiciary and the government,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He cited a case of smuggling in the city of Zhanjiang in south
China's Guangdong Province in which the municipal Party chief was
given a death sentence with a two-year reprieve; and a case in
which officials were executed for illegal dealings in the course
of the construction of a bridge that collapsed in Chongqing,
killing 40 people.
</P>
<P>
According to Han, procuratorates at all levels in China also
validated warrants for the arrests of 310,537 criminal suspects
during the first half of the year, after reviewing lists
containing 370,425 names proposed by police. Also during this
period, 282,236 suspects were brought into legal proceedings by
prosecutors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
