<HEADLINE> Second Human Rights Seminar Concludes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Second Human Rights Seminar,
jointly sponsored by China, Canada and Norway, concluded here
today in China's eastern coastal city of Qingdao.
</P>
<P>
The participants exchanged views about four topics including
the rights of ethnic minorities, the rights of laborers, freedom
of speech, and two international covenants on human rights--the
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights,
and the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights.
Hence mutual understanding was promoted and a series of agreements
on these issues reached.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi pointed out that the
seminar demonstrates the great concern the Chinese government has
for carrying out international exchanges in the field of human
rights on the basis of equality and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
Another 13 countries, from the Asian-Pacific Region, attended
the seminar as observers.
</P>
<P>
The First Human Rights Seminar was held in March last year in
Vancouver, Canada. 
</P>
