<HEADLINE> Australian Army Unveils New Communications System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Army Tuesday
unveiled a high technology digital communications systems which
will allow e-mails to be sent to the front line.
</P>
<P>
The new system will allow front line troops to communicate with
other units, their base, air support and even headquarters in
Canberra from anywhere in the world through voice, fax, and
e-mail, said Major Alison Creagh of the army's 1st Joint Support
Unit.
</P>
<P>
The 120-million-Australian dollar (79.2 million U.S. dollars)
transportable communications system, which is called Project
Parakeet, is managed by British Aerospace Australia, and designed
specifically for the Australian Defense Force.
</P>
<P>
Major General Peter Cosgrove, commander of the army's
Deployable Joint Force headquarters, said that modern armies
relied heavily on fast, reliable telephone and data transmission.
</P>
<P>
And the project had given Australia the latest technology, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Project Parakeet involves a series of vehicle-mounted modules
to provide voice, data, telegraph and facsimile services.
</P>
<P>
Project Parakeet has been tested under simulated battlefield
conditions and units in the Australian cities of Darwin,
Townsville and Brisbane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
