<P>
Although water levels are now falling, they still exceed the
danger line, and have remained there for 27 days.
</P>
<P>
Soaked with high flood waters, the river dykes have been found
to have 1,725 danger spots over the past month, the official said,
but no severe damage has been reported.
</P>
<P>
Predictions say there will be showers and strong winds tonight
to tomorrow morning across most parts of the province.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters has called for greater flood-control efforts
during the coming period of heavy rain. At present, about 350,000
civilians and soldiers are involved in flood-fighting efforts
along the dykes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK External Trade Decreases in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's re-
exports, domestic exports and imports in June 1999 all registered
year-on-year decreases according to figures released by the Census
and Statistics Department Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The value of total exports (comprising re-exports and domestic
exports) in June decreased by 5.3 percent over a year earlier to
110.6 billion HK dollars (14.2 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Within this total, the value of re-exports was down by 3.7
percent to 95.3 billion HK dollars (12.2 billion U.S. dollars),
and that of domestic exports by 13.9 percent to 15.2 billion HK
dollars (1.9 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Concurrently, the value of imports fell by 6.1 percent over a
year earlier to 115.7 billion HK dollars (14.8 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
A visible trade deficit of 5.1 billion HK dollars (654 million
U.S. dollars) was recorded in June 1999, which was smaller than
the deficit of June 1998.
</P>
<P>
For the first six months of 1999 as a whole, the value of total
exports was lower by 7.4 percent over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman noted that export
performance had improved in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the decline in export prices, total exports
should have decreased only moderately by around 3 percent in real
terms in the first half of 1999 over a year earlier, compared with
a 10 percent decline in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Underlying this improvement was the rebound in exports to a
number of East Asian markets, amidst economic recovery in the
region, according to the spokesman. The pick-up in exports to the
United States also contributed.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also noted that the decline in imports moderated
significantly in June, suggesting possibly some renewed intake of
goods for local use. Meanwhile, the visible trade deficit
continued to shrink in June as compared with a year earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
