<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clan Fighting Continues in S. Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A new armed group in Somalia,
the Digil Salvation Army (DSA), is increasing its war efforts in
and around the Qoryoley town, about 120 km south of Mogadishu, the
Somali capital, with the aim of what they called liberating the
grip of Hussein Aidid's faction from the town.
</P>
<P>
The latest such clash took place early Tuesday morning.
However, an official for Hussein Aidid had denied that any of his
men was killed in Tuesday's confrontation.
</P>
<P>
An official from Hussein Aidid's side confirmed to the press
that the leader of the attacking Garreh militiamen has been
apprehended unhurt.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the DSA has 150 armed men from the Garreh clan.
</P>
<P>
The mainly Garreh clansmen fighting in the name of DSA are the
second dominant people around the town of Qoryoley who had been
allegedly annoyed by excessive taxes imposed by the militiamen of
Hussein Mohamed Aidid for all commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
Only two days ago, the DSA launched their first attack against
the forces of Hussein Mohamed Aidid in Qoryoley town. About five
people were known to have died during that fighting.
</P>
<P>
The Garreh clansmen, mainly nomads, are believed to have had
close ties with the Ethiopian-backed Rahanwein Resistance Army
(RRA) based in Baidoa town.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid's supporters in Qoryoley town accuse the
Ethiopians for supplying weapons and military personnel to the RRA
and other Somali clans in their effort to destabilize Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Although calmness has returned to the town around noon Tuesday,
the tension is still high. More armed clashes are being expected
as the retreated DSA fighters could launch their insurgencies any
time against Hussein Aidid's men in Qoryoley town. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
