<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Visitor Markets Continue Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals continued
growing in Hong Kong, with the June total reaching 817,070, up 7.7
percent on June last year.
</P>
<P>
The figures were released Tuesday by the Hong Kong Tourist
Association (HKTA).
</P>
<P>
This was the twelfth consecutive month of growth, particularly
from key Asian markets, said Douglas Gautier, HKTA deputy
executive director.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Provided there is no setback for the rest of the year,
total arrivals in 1999 should top 10.2 million, more than six
percent above last year and almost double the growth rate forecast
at the beginning of the year."
</P>
<P>
The short-haul markets continue to produce the best results,
especially from the South and Southeast Asian countries and
Chinese mainland, helped by attractive tour pricing fueled by keen
market competition.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals in the first half of 1999 were up 11.4 percent
to just over five million, with the mainland accounting for almost
30 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong hotel average occupancy rate for the January-June
period was 77 percent, compared with 72 percent in the same period
of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
