<HEADLINE> Japan to Launch New Weather Satellite in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Japan plans to launch a multiple-use
satellite for weather forecasts and air traffic control on
September 10, the Transport Ministry and the Meteorological Agency
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the MTSAT satellite, originally planned for
August 5,was postponed to replace computer parts in the satellite,
after computer parts in a similar model were found defective,
government officials said.
</P>
<P>
The MTSAT, which is to be launched from the Tanegashima space
center in Kagoshima Prefecture, southwestern Japan, will replace
the current "Himawari" weather satellite, the officials said.
</P>
