<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Beijingers Catch Cold In Fiery Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua)-- Despite the recent heat wave, there
has been a decrease of heatstroke cases, but a staggering rise in
the number of people suffering from summer colds in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Since June 23, when a heat wave with temperatures topping 40
degrees Celsius descended north China, Xuanwu Hospital in the city
has seen a dramatic rise in the number of patients stricken with
colds.
</P>
<P>
Director Liu of the hospital's outpatient department said that
most of the patients are old people with fevers symptoms. He said
that these fevers are often induced by low indoor temperature
produced by air conditioners.
</P>
<P>
The patients remain cool at home, but are suddenly exposed to a
high temperature when they go outdoors, causing the colds.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that indoor temperatures be kept in a range of 25-
26 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
The heat wave caught Beijingers by surprise, and now swimming
pools and lakes are full of people, prompting the Beijing Daily to
say today that "it is hard to tell if there is water in the crowds,
or crowds in the water." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
