<HEADLINE> Chinese, U.S. Officials Discuss Trade (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Between January and June, U.S. technology export in contractual
volume to China stood at only 720 million US dollars, a decrease
of 15.6 percent over the same period of last year. The U.S. has
now given the position of China's number one technology exporter
to Germany.
</P>
<P>
Aaron, in his own name, expressed sorrow over the bombing of
the Chinese embassy. He said that the U.S. hopes to expand
economic and trade cooperation with China, and engage in
constructive negotiations and dialog with China.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, MOFTEC Minister Shi Guangsheng also briefly
met with Aaron. Shi said that China places great importance on
Sino-U.S. economic and trade ties, and bilateral trade and
investment in the first half of this year have both grown
vigorously. The overall trade volume between China and the U.S.
rose 11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shi said he hopes that the two countries engage in constructive
dialog based on the principles of consultations on an equal
footing and common development, so as to further promote the
development of bilateral economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
Sun and Aaron also discussed the follow-up of the 12th Session
of the Sino-US Joint Committee on Commerce and Trade (JCCT), the
protection of intellectual property rights, the U.S. Normal Trade
Relations with China and U.S. anti-dumping investigations against
Chinese products.
</P>
<P>
They agreed in principle that the 13th JCCT should be held at
an appropriate time. 
</P>
