<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sale of State-Owned Enterprises Earns Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A document available here Tuesday
from the Angolan Ministry of Industry showed that the southern
African country has obtained 42.86 million U.S. dollars through
sale of state-owned enterprises since the country implemented
privatization policy in early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Of the 80 state-owned enterprises now privatized, 42 are still
in operation while production in the rest 38 has been paralyzed,
said the document.
</P>
<P>
Currently, according to the document, the sale of 25
enterprises are still under negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Angola announced to give up socialism in 1991. Since then, the
 government has been promoting actively the privatization strategy
in the hope to alleviate its economic burdens and increase
efficiency, productivity and competitiveness of state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said the privatization progress of large
enterprises taken over from former colonialists undergoes fairly
well, whereas those mis-managed or highly-indebted medium-sized
enterprises are rarely inquired.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the fact that most of the buyers of the state-owned
enterprises are big foreign companies gives the government a
reason to worry about the declining national enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the fairness and transparency of the privatization
process, the government also resorts to public auction under
professional auction agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
