<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Makes Small Progress in Curbing Child </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has reduced child mortality
by 1.4 percent in the 15-year period from 1980 to 1996, according
to a U.N. Childrens' Fund (UNICEF) report.
</P>
<P>
The report entitled "The State of the World's Children 1998"
showed that out of every 1,000 children born alive in Kenya, at
least 90 die between birth and five years of age, ranking the
country the 55th highest among the 190 countries by the under-five
mortality rate.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is ahead of 41 of the 53 African countries in the
under-five mortality rate ranking, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The under-five mortality rates in two other east African
countries, Tanzania and Uganda, have been144 deaths and 141 per
1,000 live births respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, 11 countries in Africa are better ranked than Kenya,
with Seychelles being the best with a rate of only 19 infant
deaths per 1,000 live births. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
