<HEADLINE> Weekend Torch Festival Attracts Tourists in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Yi Autonomous Prefecture of
Chuxiong in southwest China's Yunnan Province has received over 20,
000 domestic and overseas tourists since it inaugurated the
weekend torch festival in May.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the move is to attract tourists and show them the
Yi ethnic people's customs by taking advantage of the ongoing '99
Kunming World Horticulture Exposition, which runs from May 1 to
October 31 and is expected to receive 10 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
The Torch Festival, which falls on June 24 every year according
to the Lunar Calendar, is the traditional holiday of Yi ethnic
group.
</P>
<P>
During the festival, members of the ethnic group burn torches
for three days and nights to drive away insects the legendary "
King of Heaven" sent to eat crops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yi villagers also sacrifice pigs and cows during
memorial ceremonies for their ancestors. In the evening, they walk
around their fields with torches, and gather around bonfires to
sing, dance and play musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
Chuxiong is one of the two Yi autonomous prefectures in China.
The other one is the Yi Autonomous Prefecture of Liangshan in
southwest China's Sichuan Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
