<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Arab Gulf states are expected to see their
revenues from oil exports reach some 71 billion U.S. dollars this
year, following the remarkable increase in oil prices as a result
of production cut by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
The Arab daily Al Hayat Tuesday quoted a senior economist of
the Middle East Capital Group as saying that the average price of
the North Sea Brent-type oil will reach about 16.5 dollars per
barrel in 1999 as compared to 12.7 dollars in 1998, up by 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
The oil production of the six Arab Gulf states, namely, Saudi
Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain and Oman,
was estimated at 13.1 million barrels per day this year, as
compared to 14.4 million barrels per day last year, a drop of
about 9 percent following the OPEC decision earlier this year to
cut down production.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- The Central Bank of Sudan and other commercial
banks in Khartoum will start as from August 1 to make all banking
deals in dinar rather than pound.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for the transition are under way and all banks
will be closed to the public Saturday in preparation for making
all dealings with dinars as from Sunday, the Arab daily Al Hayat
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank is due to issue small metal coins of 20-dinar
denominations for public circulation.
</P>
<P>
The dinar will be equivalent to 10 Sudanese pounds.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and the United States have agreed to establish a
joint technology project in Cairo under the name of Technology
Delta.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary amount of 50 million U.S. dollars have been
allocated for the project and the total cost was estimated at 2
billion dollars, the Arabic daily Al Hayat reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to attract U.S. investments in
technology in Egypt. And there are 22 investment projects under
consideration in various non-traditional fields, said an official
source.
</P>
<P>
The source added that the American Export-Import Bank was
currently considering providing Egypt with one billion dollars to
finance projects in the field of technology.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the second largest market in the Arab world for the
United States.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Trade volume between Egypt and the European Union (EU)
countries reached 9.8 billion euros (9.4 billion U.S. dollars) in
1998, of which exports to EU countries stood at 2.4 billion euros
(2.3 billion dollars) and imports at about 7.4 billion euros (7.1
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 1998 annual report of the EU Commission said that in
comparison with the year 1997, the EU countries saw its trade
surplus with Egypt up by about 25.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report, carried by the Egyptian daily Alam Al Yom Tuesday,
showed that the EU maintained as a major trading partner of Egypt
as it consumes about 40 percent of Egypt's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper added that finished and semi-finished products
account for the greater part of EU exports to Egypt with values
reaching about 4.1 billion euros (3.9 billion dollars), followed
by raw materials and other non-manufactured products.
</P>
<P>
As for Egypt, petroleum accounts for 40 percent of its exports
to the EU.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Tourists to Cyprus have reached 276,879 people in
June 1999 compared with 248,426 in the same month of 1998,
recording an increase of 11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals covering all categories of travelers, including
excursionists, reached 329,620 in June this year, marking an
increase of 8.8 percent from the same month last year, the Cyprus
News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The main sources of tourists are Britain, with 51.8 percent,
Sweden with 6.7 percent, Germany 5.9 percent, Russia 5 percent,
Switzerland 3.4 percent, Norway 2.8 percent and Greece 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that 78.5 percent of tourists came from
European Union member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
