<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Medical Expert On Causes of Osteoporosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Improper diet and inadequate
physical exercise are identified as the major causes of
osteoporosis that afflicts about half of elderly women in Hong
Kong, said a medical expert.
</P>
<P>
Edith Lau, an associate professor with the Chinese University
of Hong Kong (CUHK), told a press conference Tuesday that the diet
with high animal protein, high salt and low calcium is detrimental
to bones.
</P>
<P>
A CUHK research shows that the elderly who do not walk outdoors
every day are twice as likely to fall and fracture their hip than
controls, she said.
</P>
<P>
Osteoporosis, which has become 300 percent more prevalent in
Hong Kong in the last 30 years, has drawn increasing attention in
the medical study. The decease features a reduction in bone
density and makes patients easy to cause fracture.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 3,920 elderly men and women fractured their hip due to
osteoporosis and the estimated 7,641 fracture patients in 2010
would bring a major burden to the health care system in Hong Kong,
according to the CUHK research.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the prevention of osteoporosis, Lau noted
maintenance of an adequate calcium intake from childhood onwards
is important in maintaining bone density.
</P>
<P>
Absorption of calcium from green vegetables and soya products
are as good diary products, and increased intake of such foods
would be important in maintaining bone health, she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, good nutrition should be coupled with exercise, she
said, adding that the CUHK is investigating the health benefits of
the traditional Chinese exercise Tai Chi (shadow boxing).
</P>
<P>
For clinical treatment, Lau said subjects at high risk of
fracture and with extremely low bone mineral density should
definitely be treated by drugs, noting that such drugs as
alendronate have been proved very effective in preventing
fractures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
