<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The World Trade Organization in Geneva has authorized the
United States and Canada to impose a 100 percent extra customs
duty on European agricultural products such as Roquefort cheese
and omelette, after European Union refused to accept North
American beef products from hormone-fed cows.
</P>
<P>
--Algeria and Israel began to have secret contacts as early as
1980s and such contacts resumed one year ago, said a senior
Israeli diplomat. A scientists' delegation of Israel plans to
visit Algiers in the autumn this year, with an expected approval
by the Algerian government.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika met briefly with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Sunday during the funeral of
King Hassan II of Morocco. The gesture was apparently aimed at
seeking closer ties between Algeria and the United States with the
approval of Israel.
</P>
<P>
-- French enterprises France Telecom and Vivendi are seeking to
establish themselves in the English multimedia market by buying
large quantities of shares of the British media groups such as TNL
and BSkyB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
