<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Streamline Incentives for IT Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will streamline
various incentives and assistance given to the information
technology (IT) industry to enhance the IT development.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry has been directed to streamline all
efforts made together with the Multimedia Development Corporation
(MDC), the Ministry of Energy, Communications and Multimedia and
other relevant parties, Second Finance Minister Mustapa Mohamed
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Since the Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) is to be the new
growth engine, it should be given special focus and thus the
National Economic Action Council (NEAC) has asked us to look into
this," the Malaysian national news agency Bernama quoted him as
saying after launching MSC's Central Incubator in Cyberjaya near
here.
</P>
<P>
Among the incentives to be looked at in particular is the
venture capital of 120 million ringgit (31.578 million U.S.
dollars) launched last June which has received good response.
</P>
<P>
The role of the incubator is to create an environment conducive
to the development and growth of start-up IT and multimedia SMEs
within the MSC. Thus, Mustapa suggested that MSC status companies
relocate or site themselves in Cyberjaya to take full advantage of
the comprehensive and state-of-the-art infrastructure and
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The MSC Central Incubator, located on the Mutimedia University
campus, involving an investment cost of 15 million ringgit (3.947
million U.S. dollars), will also be part of the Incubator
Information Exchange that will allow the sharing of resources and
networking with other incubators in Malaysia and internationally.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has targeted 1,000 IT and multimedia SMEs in the MSC
by the year 2003 from the current 400 with a forecast that they
would reach 700 by the year 2001, according to Mustapa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
