<HEADLINE> Elect Indonesia's Leader Carefully, Says Megawati </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- General Chairman of the Indonesian
Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) Megawati Soekarnoputri
Tuesday said Indonesians should carefully make use of the People's
Consultative Assembly (MPR) to elect its leader.
</P>
<P>
"The assembly reflects the people's aspirations. Through the
assembly we will show ourselves as a civilized nation. Carefully,
elect your leader," Megawati said at the commemoration of the July
27 tragedy attended by thousands of the party's supporters.
</P>
<P>
On July 27, 1996, the Megawati-led Indonesian Democratic Party
(PDI) was attacked by a group of people. As a result, dozens of
lives were lost, some supporters of the party disappeared, dozens
of buildings and cars were damaged.
</P>
<P>
Some people made accusations that the attackers were supporters
of the Soerjadi-led PDI, and some other attackers looked like
military personnel. However, there is no final result yet from the
investigation of the case.
</P>
<P>
After the bloody incident, PDI was formally divided into two:
Soerjadi's PDI which had strong support from the government, and
Megawati's PDI which later became PDI-P and recently won the 1999
general election.
</P>
<P>
Megawati noted that an attitude of anti-violence should also be
shown during the MPR general session, and people should remember
that the assembly is owned by the whole nation.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, she said, people should close ranks for the
country's unity in the future.
</P>
<P>
During the commemoration, Megawati asked her supporters to
recall the three-year-old tragedy, which she said was an
uncivilized action.
</P>
<P>
Violence, she said, will not provide a solution, therefore
supporters of PDI-P should not be easily provoked to commit acts
of violence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chairman of the party Dimyati Hartono said if
Megawati is elected the next president, there is still a chance
for other groups to take part in the government.
</P>
<P>
During the election, PDI-P gained some 36 million votes, which
reflected the people's wish to elect Megawati their leader,
Hartono said.
</P>
<P>
However, some political elites tried to refuse the result of
the election, he added.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's highest decision-making body, will meet
in November to elect the country's next president. Megawati has
been nominated by the PDI-P for the upcoming presidential
election. She is in competition with incumbent President B.J.
Habibie, who is nominated by the Golkar Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
