<HEADLINE> Afghan Capital Hit by Rockets: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The anti-Taliban Northern
Alliance fired three rockets into the Afghan capital of Kabul
Tuesday as the factional war in the country intensified, according
to a report of the Afghan Islamic Press.
</P>
<P>
The rockets landed near Khwaja Rawash airport early Tuesday
morning, however there were no immediate reports about damage and
casualty.
</P>
<P>
Artillery exchanges between the Taliban militia and the rival
Northern Alliance have intensified north of Kabul following the
collapse of peace efforts by tribal leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban are reported to have massed 20,000 fighters in
Tagab, Najrab and Koh-e-Safi areas but neither side has committed
its infantry to the battle so far.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another report reaching here from Kabul said the
United Nations, Red Cross and Pactec group, a U.S.-based group
which transports foreign aid workers in and out of Afghanistan,
were forced to divert flights into Kabul early Tuesday after three
rockets struck the Khawaja Rawash airport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
