<HEADLINE> Fixed Asset Investments in Cambodia Fall in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia attracted 201 million
U.S. dollars in fixed asset investments in the first six months of
this year, while the total investment to Cambodia in 1998 reached
910 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures obtained from Council for the
Development of Cambodia (CDC), local companies have a 34.36
percent share in the fixed asset investment, while the foreign
investment accounts for 65.64 percent.
</P>
<P>
China has become the fourth largest foreign investor in
Cambodia this year, with an investment of 13.8 million U.S.
dollars, after Thailand with 20.5 million U.S. dollars and the
United States with 16.5 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan is on top of the investors list with 35.7 million U.S.
dollars and a share of 16.20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, which was the largest investor in 1998 with 146
million U.S. dollars capital investment, has just invested 4.2
million U.S. dollars in the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The figures show that the investment capital this year went
down although the country's stability is much better as compared
with last years.
</P>
<P>
According to a Cambodian economist, the decrease has several
factors, including the limited quota set by the United States on
garment exports and value added tax (VAT) which was implemented at
the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The CDC had approved about 50 investment projects by the end of
June this year. The garment is still the largest investment
sector, attracting 44.3 million U.S. dollars. Others include
telecommunications, hotels and agro-industry.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's garment industry has seen dramatic growth in recent
years despite the regional crisis and local political turmoil, as
investors take advantage of its export quotas. But the sector is
affected this year by limited quotas from the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
