<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Facing Defeat on "Norwegian Law" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Despite promises to support
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's plan to require ministers to resign
their Knesset (parliament) seats, a majority of Knesset factions
will vote against the move, known as the "Norwegian law."
</P>
<P>
Barak's proposal is that those next on a party's Knesset list
will replace the ministers in the Knesset, local daily The
Jerusalem Post Tuesday quoted sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
And, as a result, the legislature and executive will be
entirely independent of each other, as they are in many European
countries.
</P>
<P>
Barak's coalition agreements with the partners of the
left-wing coalition One Israel all point to the various factions'
willingness to support such a move.
</P>
<P>
However, the religious parties in the government -- Shas,
National Religious Party, and United Torah Judaism -- will oppose
any attempt to introduce the change, which would bring some 18-24
new faces into the Knesset, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Some members of Barak's One Israel are also opposed to the
plan as are several opposition parties - including the Likud,
Shinui, and members of the National Union.
</P>
<P>
Several factors are being cited by the Knesset members as the
cause of the likely rebellion against the proposal, including
that it will cost lots of money a year and that the change must
not be introduced purely to serve the interests of Barak and his
government.
</P>
<P>
The increase in Knesset members will also mean an increase in
competition for jobs in the Knesset, and then in the next party
primaries there will be more challengers.
</P>
<P>
Barak's aim was to introduce the Norwegian law alongside the
bill to expand the government's size from 18 to 24 ministers.
</P>
<P>
This would allow Barak, who assumed office early this month,
to compensate those who missed a place in the Knesset and in the
government.
</P>
<P>
Barak's political adviser Roni Bondy Monday confirmed the
prime minister's intention to introduce a Norwegian law bill
after the Knesset's summer recess. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
