<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 09:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Sees Recovery of Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The recent recovery in Egypt's
tourism sector has been reflected in investment in the country's
tourist projects, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian ministerial committee has recently approved the
implementation of 209 tourism projects, the English-language
newspaper said. It did not give details of the projects and the
time they will be put into operation.
</P>
<P>
The new projects, which are estimated to cost 5 billion
Egyptian pounds (1.47 billion U.S. dollars) will, among other
things, provide 20,000 hotel rooms. They will also create 90,000
jobs.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the aviation authority is working in
cooperation with the private sector to build airports in Mersa
Alam, Ras Sedr, Dabhaa and Alamein.
</P>
<P>
The participation of the private sector in building airports
designed to accelerate the movement of tourists in the country is
the first of its kind in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The move is viewed as part of the country's efforts to rally
support from the private sector for further improving the tourism
industry, one of the four main foreign currency earners of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's tourism suffered a heavy blow in November, 1997 when
Islamic militants killed 58 foreign visitors in the southern
resort town of Luxor, 520 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Figures showed that Egypt's tourism revenues dropped by 19.36
percent to 2.94 billion dollars in the 1997-98 fiscal year from
the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The pro-government newspaper said that Egypt has successfully
survived the crisis due to the efforts exerted by the tourism
sector and various government institutions.
</P>
<P>
The tightened security measures taken by the government in
tourist and archaeological sites across the country have played a
leading role in the campaign to overcome the challenge facing
tourism, the paper stressed.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is confident that tourist influx will be restored to its
heyday soon.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the Central Agency for Public
Mobilization and Statistics, up to 2.14 million visitors arrived
in Egypt in July to December in 1998, up by 2.8 percent from the
same period in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
