<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Auto Output Drops 3.3 Percent in First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Japan's domestic motor vehicle
output in the first half of 1999 fell 3.3 percent from the same
period of last year to 4.93 million units despite brisk exports.
</P>
<P>
Production of passenger cars, buses and trucks decreased to 4,
931,940, marking the second consecutive first-half drop from year-
earlier levels, according to Japan Automobile Manufacturers
Association.
</P>
<P>
An association official said that the shrinkage in percentage
terms, however, is a marked improvement from the 10.4 percent
contraction posted in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Domestic auto output appears to have bottomed out," the
official said, adding "both domestic auto demands and exports to
Southeast Asian countries are recovering."
</P>
<P>
In the January-June period, Japan's car output amounted to 4,
032,371, down 0.3 percent, with truck output dropping 14.9 percent
to 875,539 and bus output 20.9 percent to 24,030, the association
said.
</P>
<P>
In June, Japan's overall motor vehicle output sank 2.5 percent
from the same month last year to 858,095, down for the third
straight month from year-earlier levels, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
