<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Calls for Meaningful Dialogue With India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Tuesday reiterated his offer to India for a "meaningful
dialogue" to reduce tension and arms race in the region by
resolving the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
The talks must be "result-oriented" if India is sincere to
resolve the Kashmir issue, and it must be "without any
precondition," Sharif said during his meeting with the media in
his chamber in the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He said it is in the interest of Pakistan and India to resolve
the Kashmir issue through meaningful dialogue. The resolution of
the issue would divert precious resources for the prosperity of
the masses, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sharif noted that the tension prevailing in the region is not
in the interest of India. "New Delhi is keeping a huge army of
over 600,000 in Kashmir. Spending a huge amount on it is hampering
the country's development activities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that he had taken the decision to de-escalate the
Kargil situation in the best interest of the Pakistani nation.
Once the Kashmir problem is solved, resources of both Pakistan and
India could be diverted to economic development, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan's decision on Kargil is being appreciated.
"The ball is now in the Indian court and they must respond," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kargil has once again highlighted the urgency
to resolve the Kashmir issue, said Sharif, adding that after the
resolution of the Kashmir issue, the relations between Pakistan
and India would improve.
</P>
<P>
"Unless Kashmir issue is resolved, tension will persist,
something not good for the two countries," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
