<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PMC Holds Cautious View on Regional Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asian countries and
their ten dialogue partners Tuesday echoed a cautious attitude
toward the recent signs of economic recovery in the region.
</P>
<P>
At the opening plenary session of the Post Ministerial
Conference (PMC), many participants expressed the hope that ASEAN
and its dialogue partners should cooperate in addressing future
challenges.
</P>
<P>
Attending the two-day conference are foreign ministers from the
ten member countries of ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian
Nations) and their dialogue partners such as the United States,
China, Japan, the European Union and Russia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the PMC, Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen
Manh Cam said that Asia is now on the road to recovery, but "many
challenges remain".
</P>
<P>
The challenges include, he said, the slow and difficult
recovery process, the need of setting up social safety nets for
the poor, security issues, transboundary crimes and ASEAN's
solidarity and effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
He called on the dialogue partners to continue to cooperate
with ASEAN as the regional grouping prepares to face the
challenges.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said: "There is
still a long way to travel before we can confidently say that
we've seen a resumption of sustained economic growth in East Asia,
and there are still many potential risks."
</P>
<P>
He said that Australia welcomes the Hanoi Plan of Action (HPA)
adopted by ASEAN in 1997 as it is an ambitious range of
initiatives to hasten economic recovery and address the social
impact of the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Australia, Downer said, will continue to work with ASEAN to
help it out of the depths of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In an opening statement to the PMC, Singapore Foreign Minister
Shunmugam Jayakumar said the dialogue partners are invited to take
part in the Hanoi Plan of Action (HPA).
</P>
<P>
The HPA, said Jayakumar, is "an outward-looking plan as it
represents an open invitation to our dialogue partners to
cooperate with us in the many areas for the next six years".
</P>
<P>
"The HPA outlines the immediate and long-term priorities of
ASEAN and provides a comprehensive list of activities that ASEAN
hopes to undertake to bring us towards the ASEAN envision in the
Vision 2020," Jayakumar said.
</P>
<P>
It is the first in a series of concrete plans mapped out to
realize the Vision 2020, a long-term and broad blueprint for the
region, adopted by ASEAN leaders in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis which began two years ago has caused
severe economic damage to many Asian countries, several of them
also suffering serious and political repercussions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that many of these countries have started to
show signs of economic recovery and are recording positive growth
figures, "the reforms still need to run their course before we can
safely declare ourselves as out of the woods," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Asian countries, the crisis also affected other
regions as it is an increasingly globalized world, he said.
</P>
<P>
"To effectively resolve problems which have potential
transboundary effects, we need to work together and deal with them
collectively," he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's ten dialogue partners are Australia, Canada, China, the
European Union, India, Japan, New Zealand, Russia, South Korea and
the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
