<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Allocate  $16M for Poverty Alleviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is to spend 1.2 billion
shillings (about 16 million U.S. dollars) on poverty eradication
programs in this fiscal year, the Daily Nation newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the fiscal year from July 1 this year to June 30, 2000,
there would be no need to seek extra funds from local and external
donors if the allocation is well used, according to Kenya's
Poverty Eradication Commission.
</P>
<P>
Gilbert Oluoch, an official with the commission, said Monday
that the major task of the commission was to ensure funds meant
for reducing poverty reach the needy without disappearing halfway.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen million Kenyans, 43 percent of the east African
country's population, are reportedly living under the poverty line
of one dollar per day.
</P>
<P>
Oluoch said that the commission had earmarked some money to pay
tuition fees for children from poor families in this fiscal year,
but he noted that in the past children from rich families also got
such money.
</P>
<P>
The official revealed that an anti-poverty trust fund will be
set up for donors to contribute money and the fund will be managed
not by the government, but by a board of trustees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
