<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 08:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gap Widens Between Jewish, Arab Schools in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The gulf between Jewish and
Arab school children is widening in Israel, local daily Haaretz
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted a report published by Israeli Central Bureau
of Statistics as saying that Arab pupils and students are
discriminated against in the allocation of funds compared to
Jews.
</P>
<P>
The report relates to the years from 1990 to 1996 during both
the Likud and Labor governments.
</P>
<P>
It said Arab children studied in more crowded classrooms and
received fewer classroom hours at all educational levels.
</P>
<P>
Beyond free services provided by the government, the overall
spending on other education services for Jewish household was
greater than for an Arab household. Per Jewish household could
get 441 shekels (about 107 U.S. dollars) a year, compared to 200
shekels for an Arab household.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said the gap started to close in high
school education, with an increase in the allocation of teaching
hours to Arab schools during the period.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, a Jewish high school class was allocated 58.3 weekly
teaching hours compared to 53.9 hours for Arabs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the report claims former Likud Education Minister
Yitzhak Levy failed to implement a planned five-year program
decided on by the previous Labor government to improve Arab
education.
</P>
<P>
The new Education Minister Yossi Sarid, who took office early
this month, has said he will take positive measures to better the
lot of Arab school children.
</P>
<P>
Israel has a population of 6 million and one-fifth of it are
Arabs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
