<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Submits Budget Proposal to Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
submitted Tuesday to Congress a proposed government budget of 651
billion pesos (16.3 billion U.S. dollars) which clearly defines
the government's spending strategy for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Our spending strategy for the year 2000 calls for a more
intensified focus on strategic areas and sectors which will
ultimately make our economy robust enough to fulfill its growth
potential," the president said in his Budget Message to Congress.
</P>
<P>
Estrada cited agriculture, education, housing and local
governments as the main areas which will receive substantial
budgetary support.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, agricultural development will be
bolstered by the creation of a 21.8-billion-peso
(545-million-dollar) fund to support the implementation of the
Agriculture and Fisheries Modernization Act.
</P>
<P>
"Agricultural development is imperative not only because of its
strategic linkages in the economy but primarily because it will
help alleviate poverty," the president said.
</P>
<P>
A sum of 118 billion pesos (3 billion dollars) has been
proposed for the education sector.
</P>
<P>
"Education and skills development provide our people a chance
to participate in the opportunities offered by greater economic
activity and trade in a globalized world," the president pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
The government's housing program will be supported by 5.9
billion pesos (147.5 billion dollars), which represents an
increase of 84 percent over the 1999 allocation of 3.2 billion
pesos (80 million dollars) and intended primarily for socialized
housing.
</P>
<P>
Local governments will get a total of 131.2 billion pesos (3.28
billion dollars), with 121.8 billion pesos (3 billion dollars)
going to Internal Revenue Allotment, which represents an increase
of 26 percent from its 1999 allocation of 96.8 billion pesos (2.42
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
"We have infused more funds to local governments so that they
can have a wider leeway to extend their delivery of public
services, improve productivity, increase tax collections, and
ultimately reduce their dependence on national government
assistance," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also said that the spending strategy for next
year calls for fiscal responsibility and discipline, including
operating on a reduced budget deficit and promoting efficiency and
accountability in the use of public money.
</P>
<P>
Next year's budget deficit has been estimated to amount to 40
billion (1 billion dollars) or 1.1 percent of the Gross National
Product (GNP), compared with the 68.4 billion pesos (1.71 billion
dollars) or 2.2 percent of GNP in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
