<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Rebels Ready to Surrender to Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Rebels of the Allied Democratic
Forces fighting the government from the jungles of the Rwenzori
mountain in western Uganda have accepted the presidential pardon
and is ready to give up.
</P>
<P>
However, in a letter written to Second Division Commander of
the government army, Benon Biraro, the rebels expressed concern
over President Yoweri Museveni's recent announcement to pardon
them if they surrender before the army launches a mop-up exercise
in the jungles.
</P>
<P>
Biraro would travel to some western districts of the country to
meet those who want to surrender, the New Vision daily reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The army commander was quoted as saying that the rebels were
tired of fighting and wanted to put down their weapons and rejoin
their families.
</P>
<P>
Some of the rebels were misled and they saw no cause of
fighting against the government, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
The rebels began to fight the government from early 1996 and
have committed abductions and killings, wreaking havoc in the
western region.
</P>
<P>
The government army has tried to corner the rebels by launching
numerous mop-up exercises, leaving little room for the rebels to
manoeuvre.
</P>
<P>
During touring the northern region of the country two months
ago, President Museveni said he would pardon those rebels fighting
the government if they would like to come out and surrender before
it was too late. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
