<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices End Lower in Tokyo For 5th Straight Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices finished lower in Tokyo
for the fifth consecutive trading day Tuesday, as traders took
profits after the key Nikkei index gained some 120 points during
the morning session.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 28.62 points, or 0.16
percent, from Monday's close to end at 17,462.72.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, declined 2.21 points or 0.15 percent to 1,
434.11.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei index touched the day's high of 17,613.24 before 10
a.m., when the dollar topped 117 yen, but lost ground soon after
as the U.S. currency slipped, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Share prices were affected by movements in the foreign exchange
market throughout the day, they said.
</P>
<P>
Export-oriented blue chips were higher in early trading due to
the dollar's strength against the yen, but the issues lost their
early gains when the dollar turned down, leading the Nikkei and
the TOPIX lower, they added.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to 462.53 million shares
from 395.38 million shares Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nissan Motor was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers 698 to 483, with 130 issues ending unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
