<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian House Passes Foreign Relations Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's House of
Representatives (DPR) passed the Foreign Relations Bill in a
plenary session here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the session, House Vice Chairman Hari Sabarno said
the bill, presented by the government on April 6 this year, had
been deliberated by all factions in Commission I on law, security
and foreign affairs comprehensively.
</P>
<P>
Chairwoman of Commission I Aisyah told the session that it was
a very important instrument to boost establishment of the free and
active principle of the country's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
With the bill, she said, the House would have a greater role in
accordance with the establishment of foreign relations as such in
the matter of connecting or disconnecting diplomatic relations,
opening or closing down diplomatic representative offices and also
in the matter of deploying Indonesian peace keeping force abroad
which was previously decided by the president only.
</P>
<P>
"Now, the House will have a greater role and the government
should listen to the House opinions to decide it," she added.
</P>
<P>
Government representative Coordinating Minister of Political
and Security Affairs Feisal Tanjung said it would be a basic norm
in applications of the Indonesian foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a strong norm to boost Indonesian foreign policy
reaching its goal, also to strengthen our free and active
principle in foreign policy," Feisal said.
</P>
<P>
He said it would be the first law the Foreign Affairs
Department had and would become a guidance in conducting foreign
relations.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the bill in April, Foreign Affairs Minister Ali
Alatas said there are four main reasons for the formulation of the
bill.
</P>
<P>
First, the bill will regulate the duties, rights and
responsibilities of all Indonesians involved in foreign relations,
be they civilians or members of the government. The authority of
Indonesians abroad will be strictly monitored.
</P>
<P>
Second, the bill will provide Indonesian citizens living abroad
with better protection, because it is in line with the preamble of
the 1945 Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Third, Indonesia's goals in the international arena will only
be achieved if there is good coordination between the government
and non-governmental groups operating abroad.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, the foreign affairs minister -- being the main person
dealing with international relations -- must be supported by
credible and competent staff.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said the Foreign Relations Bill will also function as a
reference for international affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
