<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Generals In Chinese Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The People's Liberation Army (PLA)
of China has had 13 generals from Tibet over the past 50 years,
military sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Most of them came from serf families and rose up through the
ranks. As early as in 1955, when the PLA introduced the military
rank system, 5 Tibetans were given the rank of major general or
lieutenant general.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, 8 more Tibetan officers were given the rank of major
general. All of them were the children of poor serfs.
</P>
<P>
Garma Cedain became famous for marksmanship and horsemanship
and was considered both intelligent and courageous. He was made
deputy commander of a military area command at the age of 35 and
later became a major general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
