<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Egyptian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Egyptian newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahram:
</P>
<P>
-- Egypt and Turkey are the two mainstays of stability in the
region, visiting Turkish President Suleyman Demirel told Egypt TV
on Monday. Demirel said Egypt is undertaking a constructive and
tangible role in the regional peace process.
</P>
<P>
Al-Akhbar:
</P>
<P>
-- Suez Canal Authority Chairman Ahmed Fadel said the Suez
Canal returns have grown remarkably due to increase in the oil
prices and so rise in the number of oil tankers crossing the
Canal. The toll rose to 193 million U.S. dollars following duties
cuts on ships crossing the Canal.
</P>
<P>
Al-Gomhuria:
</P>
<P>
-- All computers in Egypt will be adapted by September 30 and
alternative plans will be drawn to meet any emergency, said Ehab
Elwy, Chairman of the Central Agency for General Mobilization and
Census, who is in charge of a technical committee on adapting
computers for the Year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Monday expressed renewed
optimism over prospects for the Middle East peace process with the
new Israeli government of Prime Minister Ehud Barak. "The present
situation encourages us to be optimistic and there will always be
hope in peace," Mubarak told reporters after he inaugurated the
new Moharam Bey Flyover in Egypt's largest port city of
Alexandria. 
</P>
