<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Passes Bill to Regulate Power to Borrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Parliament Tuesday
passed the Statutory Bodies (Power to Borrow) Bill 1999 to
regulate the power to borrow by statutory bodies established by
the federal law, their companies and corporations.
</P>
<P>
Under the provisions of the bill passed in the House of
Representatives without debate, a statutory body, its company or
corporation, will not be allowed to take loans without prior
approval of the finance minister.
</P>
<P>
Tabling the bill, Deputy Finance Minister Mohamed Nazri Aziz
said that at present there was no uniformity among the statutory
bodies, their companies and corporations on the power to borrow.
</P>
<P>
The bill enables the Finance Ministry to obtain detailed
information on the amount of debts and loans applied by the
statutory bodies and their companies.
</P>
<P>
According to Mohamed Nazri, there are now 400 companies set up
by the federal statutory bodies with 50 percent equity in 23 of
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
