<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Anticipates East Timor Ballot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Coordinating Minister of Political
and Security Affairs Feisal Tanjung Tuesday said the Indonesian
government had been anticipating any result of the East Timor
direct ballot scheduled for August 21 or 22.
</P>
<P>
"We anticipate on the matter, of course," Feisal told reporters
after a session with the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
He said whether East Timor would remain a part of Indonesia or
become independent, the Indonesian government had made
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to disclose what anticipation the
government had made.
</P>
<P>
"You needn't know that," he said, citing it was a government
authority to do so.
</P>
<P>
Asked what would the Indonesian government do if
pro-integration group lose in the ballot, Feisal said: "Who said
that (prediction). Let East Timorese make decision. We'll
appreciate whatever they will be decided."
</P>
<P>
Under a United Nations-brokered agreement with Portugal,
Indonesia agreed to hold a direct ballot in August. The ballot
will allow the territory's people to choose whether their homeland
should become an autonomous region within Indonesia or totally
independent.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
