<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Have New Bank Notes in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Two banks in Macao will have new
bank notes printed before Macao's power transfer from Portugal to
China and the notes will be put into circulation on December 20.
</P>
<P>
Approved by the Macao Currency and Foreign Exchange Authority,
the Macao branch of the Bank of China and Macao branch of
Portuguese Banco Nacional Ultramarino will share the issuance of 2.
2 billion patacas (275 million U.S. dollars) half-and-half.
</P>
<P>
The two banks joined hands to issue bank notes for the first
time in 1995 and they agreed that each would undertake half of the
new bank note issuance.
</P>
<P>
Some bank notes have worn out over the past several years and
the 10-pataca notes were put out of circulation not long ago. As a
result, the monetary market demands new notes, according to
sources with the Macao branch of the Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
With the new century approaching, the two banks have to prepare
enough cash to cope with public worries about the millennium
computer bug.
</P>
<P>
The overall design of the new bank notes will remain unchanged
except for the new issuance date and signatures of bank heads. It
is believed that part of the new bank notes may go to the hands of
money collectors because the issuance will coincide with China's
resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Budget for 2000 Free From Pork Barrel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government's
proposed 651-billion-peso (16.3-billion-U.S.-dollar) budget for
the year 2000 would remain free of any form of pork barrel, a
ranking official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Benjamin Diokno of the Department of Budget and
Management said in a radio interview that the new budget would not
allow lawmakers to get their hands on funds intended for priority
pro-poor programs.
</P>
<P>
"Projects are integrated in the budgets of the concerned
departments. The money is relegated to line agencies, not to the
congressmen," Diokno said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Philippine President Joseph Estrada stressed lawmakers
can only identify priority projects for funding under the budget,
and only so long as these conform to the government's pro-poor
thrusts.
</P>
<P>
Diokno said the proposed 2000 budget would be "closely linked"
to the national budgets in the succeeding years to support the
Estrada administration's five-year medium term development plan.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 budget, he explained, was designed more to lay the
foundation for the country's sustained development.
</P>
<P>
"It allowed us to establish the foundation for 2000. In the
2000 budget, there will be more resources for priority areas," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Diokno belied claims by some sectors that the 1999
budget failed to produce tangible results.
</P>
<P>
He said the first quarter of 1999 saw a seven percent growth in
government consumption expenditures and a 20 percent hike in
public construction.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts at pump-priming the economy, he said,
contributed to the two percent growth in the Gross National
Product in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Estrada presented to Congress Tuesday the proposed
651-billion-peso (16.3-billion-U.S.-dollar) budget for year 2000
focusing on four areas -- agriculture, education, housing and
local governance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
