<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Upgrade Nuke Arms if U.S. Breaches ABM Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia has threatened to upgrade
its nuclear forces and take "other asymmetric measures" if the
United States violates the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, the Itar-
Tass news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The threat, from an unidentified Russian Defense Ministry
expert, came after U.S. President Bill Clinton signed a bill on
the development of a national anti-ballistic missile system, a
move that has prompted criticisms from around the world.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the bill was a sign of double standards in the
American diplomacy, the Defense Ministry expert said.
</P>
<P>
He accused Washington of "working and taking practical steps
which do not simply contradict the spirit and aims of the ABM
treaty but openly lead to its destruction."
</P>
<P>
U.S. calls to modify the ABM treaty were in fact attempts to
emasculate the 1972 treaty and legalize its activity in the field
of the anti-ballistic missile defenses, the expert said.
</P>
<P>
"If, in defiance of the common sense, the United States
continues its line of deployment of a national ABM system, which
we do not want, Russia will be forced to engage in the perfecting
of its strategic nuclear forces and the taking of other asymmetric
measures designed to raise its national security in new military-
strategic conditions," the expert warned.
</P>
<P>
"Russia was and remains a country of high technologies," he
said. "No one should have any doubts on this count." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
