<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 07:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Population Growth Expected to Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The population growth of the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) is expected to slow down in the first
five years of next millennium, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2005, the country's population growth rate will
fall from 6.5 percent to 2.9 percent, and the number of people
living in the UAE is expected to grow from the present 2.94
million to 3.48 million, says the study on development indicators
in the UAE, which was quoted by the Gulf News on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Issued by the Abu Dhabi Crown Prince's Court, the study
contains comprehensive data covering the years from 1975 to 1998,
which make it a main reference document for researchers,
investors and decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
It shows that the workforce in the UAE has grown from 288,414
in 1975 to 1,378,390 last year, and the type of work people are
doing is changing.
</P>
<P>
In 1975, the largest sector was construction, which accounted
for 26 percent of the work force, followed by the wholesale,
retail, restaurant and hotel sector, which made up 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, however, the wholesale, retail,
restaurant and hotel sector was the largest, making up 22 percent
of the workforce, pushing construction into second place with 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 percent of the workforce is based in Abu Dhabi, which
is followed by Dubai and Sharjah, with 30 percent and 15 percent
respectively, the study says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Mining Earnings Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's mining earnings decreased
in the first five months of this year to 205.3 million U.S.
dollars from 282.07 million dollars recorded in the same period of
last year, according to the Financial Mail weekly.
</P>
<P>
The statistics released by the Finance Ministry showed that
copper earnings fell by 37 percent while cobalt earnings rose by
15 percent in the five months.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, copper exports earned the southern
African country 143.3 million dollars, 61 million dollars came
from the cobalt exports and the remaining was from the exports of
other metals such as gold and silver.
</P>
<P>
Mining earnings dropped partly due to falling copper prices on
the international market because of low demand in Asia.
</P>
<P>
During the five months, the total volume of finished copper
production fell slightly to 116,343 tons from 116,811 tons
registered during the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The decline in export earings of the mining industry could make
the copper-producing country need more external financing.
</P>
</TEXT>
