<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Conflict Derails Zambia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The one-year conflict in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) has dragged down Zambia's
non-traditional exports by three percent because of the dwindling
demand of building materials in the DRC, Rwanda and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's earnings from non-traditional exports have declined by
three percent from 90.48 million dollars in the same period of
last year to 87 million dollars in the first four months of this
year, the Zambian Financial Mail newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The directorate of macro-economics policy analysis in the
Ministry of Finance and Economic Development said in its the Real
Sector Report for May that the fall in non-traditional exports
earnings has been evident in building materials.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from building materials have fallen by 47 percent from
2.98 million dollars registered in the first four months of 1998
to 1.6 million dollars this year because of reduced demand in the
DRC, Burundi and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a source close to the Export Board of
Zambia as saying that the DRC, which has previously been the
country's regional biggest export market, is now second with more
exports from Zambia going to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, for instance, exports to the DRC amounted to 32.8
million U.S. dollars while those to South Africa totalled 28.8
million dollars, but the situation has changed in the past two
years with exports to South Africa reaching 57.7 million last year
while those to the DRC were 38.4 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
