<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Population Quality Stressed in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Family planning administrative departments have a duty to
enhance the quality of the Chinese people," according to Yang
Kuifu, vice-minister of the State Family Planning Commission (SFPC)
.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamental task of family planning is to control the
growth of the population and improve the quality of the people,"
he told a national meeting on the dissemination of scientific
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goal, the SFPC is to make more scientific
information on family planning available in the next few years,
according to the country's English-language newspaper China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China has 130 million illiterate and semi-illiterate
people, and 60 million disabled. About 1.3 percent of the babies a
year are born with defects.
</P>
<P>
The SFPC has mapped out a blueprint for population and family
planning work in the next half-century. It sets targets for
providing minimum reproductive health care services for couples of
a reproductive age by next year and basic services by 2010.
</P>
</TEXT>
