<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Major Vocational Guidance Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's biggest vocational
guidance program was launched Tuesday to further decrease
unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to provide information on vocational courses
which would help the unemployed youth to find jobs easily in the
future, a Labor Department spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
A number of mercantile and state sector institutions took part
in the program to create an awareness among the participants about
available vocational courses relating to the fields of computing,
accountancy, management, jewelry and electronics.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's unemployment rate fell to 9.1 percent of the labor
force in 1998 from 10.4 percent the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate fell steadily, considering the rate of 12.3
percent in 1995, 13.8 percent in 1993 and 15.9 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
However, a recent study conducted by the Labor Department
reveals that the majority of unemployed youth in the country who
possess better educational qualifications are still among the
unemployed due to their lack of knowledge on certain employment
avenues.
</P>
<P>
The program is open to parents as well for them to know about
the jobs that their children are going to do according to their
educational qualifications and abilities. 
</P>
