<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Divorce Rate in Shanghai up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 27 (Xinhua)-- A more open and tolerant society
has resulted in a growth in the divorce rate in the metropolitan
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The Yangpu District civil affairs bureau approved divorces for
1,650 couples last year, 2.6 times the number in 1989 and 33.3
times that of 1979.
</P>
<P>
A survey the bureau did last year found that 36 percent of the
respondents cited incompatibility and 22 percent, extramarital
affairs, as the cause of divorce. Drug addiction and excessive
gambling or dancing were blamed for 12 percent of the failed
marriages.
</P>
<P>
Wang Haiyan, the bureau's division chief, says that people of
Shanghai have become more demanding about their sex life in
marriage and that those divorces resulting from "incompatible
character" are in many cases due to an inharmonious sex life.
</P>
<P>
Xu Anqi, an expert on marriage at the Shanghai Academy of
Social Sciences says that the rise in divorce rate is normal and
understandable and that the demand for quality in a marriage
should be respected.
</P>
<P>
She says that China's divorce rate is still quite low when
compared to the West. A recent study showed 0.5 percent of Chinese
women in the age range of 25-44 divorced and that ranks 121st in a
listing of 129 countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
