<HEADLINE> Fall in Gold Prices Leads to High Sales in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The steady fall in gold prices
in the world markets over the last few weeks has brought good
business to jewelry shops in the United Arab Emirates (UAE), a
newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The recent decline in gold prices, following the sale of vast
reserves of gold by countries like Britain and South Africa, and
the proposed sale of bullion by Switzerland, has led customers to
crowd into various jewelry outlets in the UAE, said the
Dubai-based Khaleej Times daily.
</P>
<P>
The customers want to avail themselves of the crashing prices,
which are at a 20-year low, the paper quoted jewelry store owners
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most shops have seen a 30 percent increase in their usual
summer sale, said Tushar Patni, President of the Abu Dhabi Gold
and Jewelry Group.
</P>
<P>
"It is for this reason that we have decided not to have the
Abu Dhabi Gold Festival this year, because business is already
good," he added.
</P>
<P>
He anticipated that a steady decline in gold prices by 3-4
percent until the end of the year was likely, before prices
started steadying again.
</P>
<P>
Studies show that at least 65 percent of the population in the
UAE buy gold at one time or another, and the per capita
requirement is one ounce, which equals 35 grams. Arabs and
Indians are the biggest buyers of gold in this country.
</P>
<P>
The UAE imported about 26.7 tons of gold in the first quarter
of this year, compared to 25.3 tons in the same period last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
