<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese City Tries New Measures to Reduce Housing Stockpiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 27 (Xinhua) --Fuzhou, the capital of China's
Fujian Province, plans to develop ways to encourage the city's
sluggish real estate market.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, they will include lowering prices
for apartments on the market, simplifying procedures for getting
housing loans, and rescinding rules that limit the sales of state-
subsidized apartments on secondary markets.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, 1.59 million sq.m. of
apartments were sold, worth about 2.06 billion yuan, according to
the Fuzhou City Real Estate Administration.
</P>
<P>
However, there are still 734,000 sq.m. of apartments, office
space, and other space on the market. China has long suffered from
a nationwide glut of apartment dwellings and different places are
being encouraged to try different ways to help reduce the
stockpile.  
</P>
</TEXT>
