<HEADLINE> U.S. Goes on as Winnipeg Celebrates Its Own Triumphs ( Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Perennial powerhouse the
United States scored a nine-gold day in the Pan Am medal chase as
Winnipeg athletes gave the center Canadian city more reasons to
celebrate on Day Three of the continental tournament.
</P>
<P>
The Americans rushed golds in karate, gymnastics, equestrian,
rowing shooting and table tennis, lifting the medals tally to 63
with 24 golds, 24 silvers and 15 bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Cuba fell short of 7 golds, settling down at the second spot
with a 15-11-11 record. Hosts Canada held on at the third with 9
golds, 9 slivers and 16 bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Winnipegger Emma Robinson and her partner Theresa Luke battled
stiff winds and whitecaps to win the women's coxless pairs rowing
title while Winnipeg-born Tracy Duncan struck silver in the
lightweight competitions, thrilling a big crowd packing around the
Lake Minnedasa on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Robinson and Luke, top finishers from yesterday's qualification,
led from start to finish down the 2000-meter course, sweeping the
title in 7:38.53, with American pairs Karen-Marie Kraft and Missy
Ryan placing a well-beaten second at 7:46.64.
</P>
<P>
Duncan, 27, failed to maintained the lead in yesterday's women'
s lightweight single scull heat event over Argentine Maria Julia
Garisoain, finishing second with 8:06.31 to Garisoain's 8:04.50,
but the adoring home fans were cheered up all the same.
</P>
<P>
Men's coxless pairs event yielded another gold for Argentina,
with Damian Ordas and Walter Balunek kicking up in the last 500m
to beat Brazilian pairs Alexandre Soares and Gibran Cunha and
wrapping up the title in 6:40.49. The Brazilians were at 6:40.75
for the silver.
</P>
<P>
In the men's lightweight single scull, American William Belden
won the race in 7:23.51, with Cuban Martin Hernandez second at 7:
26.59.
</P>
<P>
Later today, table tennis' team competitions yielded a pair of
golds for the United States, with American men edging out
Argentina 3-2 and women cruising to a 3-0 win.
</P>
<P>
Mexico had a big show-off at the Pan Am 20km walk race as
Bernardo Segura slashed more than two minutes off the Games record
to win the men's event in one hour 20 minutes 17 seconds and his
teammate, the 36-year-old veteran M. Mendoza took the women's won
the titles in 1:34:19.
</P>
<P>
Morgan White of the United States claimed the women's
gymnastics all-around title by skin of the teeth here on Monday,
totaling 37.649 points to hold off heavily-favored Canadian
Michelle Conway by a slender margin of 0.031 points.
</P>
<P>
Matthew Emmons shot down another gold for the United States,
collecting 104.0 points to win the men's free rifle prone title.
</P>
<P>
In the volleyball preliminaries, the United States scored a
scared 20-25, 25-17, 16-25, 25-19, 15-12 win over underdogs
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Carribean country Netherlands Antilles got off to the medals
table here today, with Anthony Boelbaai winning karate's up to 70
kg event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
