<HEADLINE> Northwestern China Holding Grape Festival in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The 9th Silk Road Grape Festival
will be held in Turpan Prefecture in China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region from August 26 to 30.
</P>
<P>
The first grape festival was held in 1990 to mark the 2,100th
anniversary of the Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
The focus of this year's festival is economic and trade talks,
as has been the case at previous festivals, but there will be
theatrical performances as well. The prefecture has decided to
spend more than 10 million yuan on tourist facilities to attract
more visitors.
</P>
<P>
Turpan is an ancient city that was a political, economic, and
cultural center for western parts of China in the old days. It was
one of the first cities in the region that were approved by the
State Council for opening to the outside world (in 1978).
</P>
<P>
Thanks to its grape festivals, it has connections with many
provinces, regions, and cities in China and with more than 140
countries. It has long been known for its grapes, particularly the
seedless white, red, and purple grapes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
