<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0430 GMT, July 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine government plans to impose another
round of bank capital increases after an ongoing campaign is
completed by end-2000, Journal newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu as saying a
further adjustment is necessary to further insulate the local
financial system from external shocks and give local banks more
muscle to compete on a regional scale. (Philippines-Bank Capital)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Representatives from 34 American countries held
bilateral meetings in Cochabamba, central Bolivia, on Monday ahead
of a regional gathering on July 28-30 to review progress in
shaping the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
They will attend the third meeting of the Committee of Trade
Negotiations (CTN) of the FTAA on July 28-30 to evaluate
differences between the economies of the participating countries,
reports reaching here quoted Bolivian Foreign Ministry as saying.
(Americas-Free Trade-Meetings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The European Union (EU) will provide 8.8 million U.S.
dollars for "a Regional Reconstruction Program for Central America,
" Nicaragua's Foreign Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the Foreign Ministry said that the
program was approved by the EU to help Central American countries
affected by hurricane "Mitch" carry out analyses of damage brought
about by the disaster last October and to implement reconstruction
projects. (CAmerica-EU-Donation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Hong Kong's export to Panama's Free Zone of
Colon (FZC) will reach 1.2 billion U.S. dollars by the end of 1999,
the zone's statistic data showed.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Hong Kong and Panama through the free zone in
1996 totaled 1.365 billion dollars. (HK-Panama-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the National
Association of Manufacturers (NAM) on Monday urged the House of
Representatives to maintain normal trading relations with China,
which they view as vital to promoting American business and
consumer interests in the days to come.
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining open ties with China is critical for businesses in
every corner of this country," U.S. Chamber of Commerce President
and CEO Thomas J. Donohue said, quoting trade data as showing that
about 200,000 jobs and 18 billion U.S. dollars in exports depend
on trade with China. (US-China-NTR)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam's trade deficit in the first seven months of
this year has plunged on the back of an export recovery, Vietnam's
English daily Vietnam News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's deficit now stands at 167 million U.S. dollars, a
colossal decline of 1.2 billion dollars from the same period of
last year, according to Vietnam's General Statistics Office (GSO).
(Vietnam-Trade Deficit) 
</P>
</TEXT>
