<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Urges Dialogue Partners to Join Regional Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) Tuesday called on its 10 dialogue partners
to participate in a regional development plan.
</P>
<P>
In the opening statement to the Post Ministerial Conference
(PMC), Singapore Foreign Minister shunmugam Jayakumar said the
dialogue partners are invited to take part in the Hanoi Plan of
Action (HPA).
</P>
<P>
The HPA, said Jayakumar, is "an outward-looking plan as it
represents an open invitation to our dialogue partners to
cooperate with us in the many areas for the next six years."
</P>
<P>
"The HPA outlines the immediate and long-term priorities of
ASEAN and provides a comprehensive list of activities that ASEAN
hopes to undertake to bring us toward the ASEAN vision in the
Vision 2020," Jayakumar said.
</P>
<P>
The HPA is the first in a series of concrete plans mapped out
to realize the Vision 2020, a long-term and broad blueprint for
the region, adopted by ASEAN leaders in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The plan includes measures to deal with the financial crisis
and its fallout, transnational issues, as well as many other
important subjects, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the challenge facing ASEAN now is to continue to adhere
to the reforms against the backdrop of "glimmers of hope on the
horizon."
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis which began two years ago has caused
severe economic damage to many Asian countries, several of them
also suffering serious and political repercussions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that many of these countries have started to
show signs of economic recovery and are recording positive growth
figures, "the reforms still need to run their course before we can
safely declare ourselves as out of the woods," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Asian countries, the crisis also affected other
regions as it is an increasingly globalized world, he said.
</P>
<P>
"To effectively resolve problems which have potential
transboundary effects, we need to work together and deal with them
collectively," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the future direction of PMC, Jayakumar suggested that some
follow-up mechanism will be established so as to provide
continuity and direction to what was discussed at the previous
PMC.
</P>
<P>
"Various suggestions have been made," he said, citing as an
example the proposal that dialogue partners may work with the
various ASEAN sectoral subcommittees to follow up on their
specific proposals.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, he said, the foreign ministers at the PMC
will discuss the future of the conference during "an extended
lunch," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is to allow the ministers an opportunity to
brainstorm on how to revitalize the Post Ministerial Conferences
and the dialogue relationships," he said.
</P>
<P>
The PMC followed the 32nd ASEAN Ministerial Meeting on July 23
and 24 and the ASEAN Regional Forum on July 26. Singapore, as the
current ASEAN chairman, presides over all these meetings.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's 10 dialogue partners are Australia, Canada, China, the
European Union, India, Japan, New Zealand, Russia, South Korea and
the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
