<HEADLINE> South China City Increasing Intellectual Property Rights Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, the capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, has beefed up efforts to protect
intellectual property rights this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, 770,000 pirated compact discs and 880,
000 illegal audio-video publications were confiscated, according
to the city's Press and Publications Administration.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has been in the forefront in China's reforms and
opening-up and is a doorway for the interior to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
From January to June, public security officers working with the
administration raided eight major storehouses of pirated
electronic publications and effectively stopped illegal electronic
publications at the source and helped guard normal market order,
the Administration says. 
</P>
