<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Urges Investigation Into Kosovo Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
called for a speedy and thorough investigation Monday into the
massacre of 14 Serb villagers in Yugoslavia's province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The council "strongly condemns this criminal act" and calls for
an investigation to bring all those responsible to justice, said a
statement issued after a council meeting which ended Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The 15 members of the council said they were "deeply shocked
and gravely concerned" at the incident.
</P>
<P>
They support international efforts to ensure peace and security
for all inhabitants of Kosovo. The meeting was convened at the
request of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to the council president dated July 24, Yugoslav
Charge d'Affaires Vladislav Jovanovic described Friday's massacre
of 14 Serb farmers near the village of Gradsko as "the latest and
most ruthless in a series of atrocities" committed by the Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA).
</P>
<P>
The 78-day NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia produced some
900,000 refugees from the Serb province.
</P>
<P>
So far some 730,000 refugees have returned home, while another
170,000 Serbs from Kosovo are displaced, according to U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Sadako Ogata on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Retaliation and revenge must not be allowed to prevail" in
Kosovo, she told the U.N. Security Council when dealing with the
refugee problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
