<HEADLINE> India to Double Investment in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- India is planning to double its
investment in Sri Lanka to 100 million U.S. dollars by the year
2000, official sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A study conducted by the Indian Federation of Chambers has
confirmed this figure, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The investment will be mainly in textiles, cement production,
leather, plastic products and dairy products.
</P>
<P>
At present 42 Indian projects with a total investment of 28
million dollars are already in operation in Sri Lanka while 10
more projects at a cost of 23 million dollars are under
construction.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have agreed to open their economies by the
year 2005 under the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the new investments and the recently
signed free trade agreement between the two countries will prepare
them for trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also have between them a considerable trade
and economic agenda which will contribute to their economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Recently Indian High Commissioner in Sri Lanka Shivshankar
Menon told a business gathering that Sri Lanka was already India's
preferred investment destination in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Fifty percent of India's joint ventures and wholly-owned
subsidiaries in South Asia are in Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
