<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Business Groups Urge House to Support NTR With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Chamber of Commerce
and the National Association of Manufacturers (NAM) on Monday
urged the House of Representatives to maintain normal trading
relations with China, which they view as vital to promoting
American business and consumer interests in the days to come.
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining open ties with China is critical for businesses in
every corner of this country," U.S. Chamber of Commerce President
and CEO Thomas J. Donohue said, quoting trade data as showing that
about 200,000 jobs and 18 billion U.S. dollars in exports depend
on trade with China.
</P>
<P>
Donohue made the appeal just before the House is to vote on a
bill concerning Normal Trade Relations (NTR) with China on Tuesday.
He called on the House to vote for the NTR, a move he described as
"the right step for American business, workers and consumers."
</P>
<P>
"As China offers to open its vast markets as part of its bid to
join the World Trade Organization (WTO), U.S. exports are poised
to grow tremendously. A strong House vote on NTR is important to U.
S. negotiators' efforts to secure a WTO deal that will benefit
American business," Donohue said.
</P>
<P>
He noted "a policy of engagement with China promotes U.S.
interests on issues of vital importance, including security, non-
proliferation, the rule of law, and human rights as well as trade.
"
</P>
<P>
The Chamber, the world's largest business federation
representing over three million businesses and organizations of
every size, has been working hard to mobilize grassroots support
for China's NTR.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 115 state and local Chambers of Commerce
around the country have joined the U.S. Chamber-led "Chambers for
China Trade," an expanding group aimed at boosting U.S. trade with
China, said a news release from the Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
It will also continue to press for permanent NTR status for
China upon conclusion of a commercially meaningful WTO agreement
between Washington and Beijing, Donohue said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Dianne Sullivan, NAM director of trade policy, said
in a press release that "normal trading relations is not a favor
we are doing for China, it's a favor we are doing for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. economic health and expansion depends upon selling to
markets outside of our own," Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
China, with one-quarter of the world's population, has a market
that offers "enormous potential for U.S. companies" and may bring
about "high paying, quality jobs, shareholder and retiree profits
and competitiveness" in the United States, she added.
</P>
<P>
Sullivan emphasized that cutting off normal trade relations
will only cede China's market to America's international
competitors, and hamper critical efforts to get China into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"It would be foolish and more than a little dangerous for the
most powerful country in the world to simply 'disengage' from the
most populous country in the world," she said.
</P>
<P>
As Congress prepares to vote on the NTR, U.S. lawmakers are
finding themselves bombarded by full-page ads and articles from
their hometown newspapers, as well as e-mails from business and
many other communities, calling for increased trade links with
China.
</P>
<P>
"There has not been an issue more heavily lobbied," the
Associate Press quoted Rep. Sherrod Brown, D-Ohio, as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the AP, each lawmaker has received a letter
recently from the Chamber of Commerce with state-to-state
statistics showing the value of trade with China. Citing as
examples, the figures from New York stood at 679 million dollars
in goods exported in 1998, and those of California 2.4 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0275 </DOCNO>
