<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Trade Deficit Plunges, Export Recovers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's trade deficit in the first
seven months of this year has plunged on the back of an export
recovery, Vietnam's English daily Vietnam News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's deficit now stands at 167 million U.S. dollars, a
colossal decline of 1.2 billion dollars from the same period of
last year, according to Vietnam's General Statistics Office (GSO).
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's exports over the first seven months rose 12.2 percent
to 6.166 billion dollars due to increased shipments of shoes and
higher oil prices, said GSO.
</P>
<P>
Imports of the country for the period fell 8.3 percent to 6.333
billion dollars, with the fall blamed on a downturn in foreign
direct investment and fragile domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Some 12 out of 15 Vietnamese major exports posted positive
growths.
</P>
<P>
Footwear exports grew 32.1 percent while textile and garment
exports increased 7.6 percent. Volume exports of oil, the
country's third largest export, rose 26.7 percent during the
period.
</P>
<P>
Exports of rice, Vietnam's top agricultural export, increased 5
percent in the year to date.
</P>
<P>
Other exports fell, including tea, down 6.2 percent; cashew,
38.8 percent; and groundnuts, 42.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-invested enterprises' exports grew 20.3 percent to 1.38
billion dollars while their imports grew 8.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Motorbike imports fell 13.9 percent and those of automobile and
spare parts 36.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Cement clinker imports fell 56.2 percent to 245,000 tons, with
zero imports of cement recorded during July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
