<HEADLINE> Philippines Fast-Tracks Airport Development Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
fast-tracking the development of airports nationwide worth 18.65
billion pesos (466 million U.S. dollars) to meet the deadline of
2004, a ranking official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Vicente Rivera, secretary of the Department of Transportation
and Communication (DOTC), said in a report that DOTC's thrust is
to develop one airport of international standards in each of the
administrative regions.
</P>
<P>
Rivera said DOTC, through the Air Transportation Office (ATO),
plans to expand existing runways, construct terminals and upgrade
facilities for night operations.
</P>
<P>
ATO is also encouraging the development of rural air transport
facilities so that small carriers can serve routes normally
thought of as unprofitable by the bigger airlines, Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Philippines has four international airports,
four alternate international airports, 12 trunkline airports and
36 secondary and 33 feeder airports.
</P>
<P>
A majority of the development projects of ATO are being backed
up by multilateral funding agencies and lending institutions,
Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that several lending agencies, such as the Asian
Development Bank and the European Investment Bank, are infusing
funds for the development of the different airports nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
