<HEADLINE> Preparatory Meetings Begin for Free Trade Area of Americas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from 34
American countries held bilateral meetings in Cochabamba, central
Bolivia, on Monday ahead of a regional gathering on July 28-30 to
review progress in shaping the Free Trade Area of the Americas (
FTAA).
</P>
<P>
They will attend the third meeting of the Committee of Trade
Negotiations (CTN) of the FTAA on July 28-30 to evaluate
differences between the economies of the participating countries,
reports reaching here quoted Bolivian Foreign Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, the participants will discuss tariff issues
at the meeting of CTN, which was created by the Santiago de Chile
Summit in April 1998 in a bid to overcome the obstacles to the
creation of a free trade area in the Americas in 2005.
</P>
<P>
Hosted by Bolivian Foreign Minister Javier Murillo, the
Cochabamba meeting is expected to prepare a report for the trade
ministerial meeting to be held in Toronto, Canada, next October.
