<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Doctors Concerned Over Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan medical authorities are
concerned over air pollution in the country's capital city and has
urged the government to take action to reduce the pollution, media
sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A recent study on air pollution by a team of doctors has
revealed that air pollution in certain parts of the city is far
above the maximum permissible levels stipulated by the World
Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued by the doctors, data on the
quality of ambient air in the city of Colombo was reviewed
together with blood lead levels of children living in close
proximity to a junction with heavy traffic throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
Fifty of the children between one and 15 years of age had blood
samples for lead levels by Atomic Absorption Spectrometry.
Demographic, environmental, behavioral factors and
neuro-development were also investigated, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Ambient air in certain areas in Colombo and lead levels above
permissible standards by the WHO were detected. Elevated lead
levels were found in traffic policemen and children who were
screened.
</P>
<P>
Children in particular inhale a proportionally larger air
volume, have a higher gut absorption rate of lead and are
particularly vulnerable to excessive lead, the sources added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
