<HEADLINE> Winnipeg Thrilled by Local Heroines' Rowing Triumph </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Winnipegger Emma Robinson
and her partner Theresa Luke battled stiff winds and whitecaps to
win the Pan Am gold in the women's coxless pairs rowing event
while Tracy Duncan, also born in the center Canadian city, struck
silver in the lightweight competitins, thrilling a big crowd
packing around the Lake Minnedasa here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Robinson and Luke, top finishers from yesterday's qualification,
led from start to finish down the 2,000-meter course, sweeping the
title in 7:38.53, with Amercian pairs Karen-Marie Kraft and Missy
Ryan placing a well-beaten second at 7:46.64.
</P>
<P>
The Canadians looked so impressive on the water that Dolores
Young, Manitoba Rowing Association executive director heaped
praises on them.
</P>
<P>
"They just row so well, those two. Technically, they are
fabulous," he said to the reporters.
</P>
<P>
Duncan, 27, failed to maintained the lead in yesterday's women'
s lightweight single scull heat event over Argentine Maria Julia
Garisoain, finishing second with 8:06.31 to Garisoain's 8:04.50,
but the adoring home fans were cheered up all the same.
</P>
<P>
The former local Grant Park High School student was also beaten
by the Argentine in last year's World Championships.
</P>
<P>
Men's coxless pairs event yielded another gold for Argentina,
with Damian Ordas and Walter Balunek kicking up in the last 500m
to beat Brazilian pairs Alexandre Soares and Gibran Cunha and
wrapping up the title in 6:40.49. The Brazilians were at 6:40.75
for the silver.
</P>
<P>
In the men's lightweight single scull, American William Belden
won the race in 7:23.51, with Cuban Martin Hernandez second at 7:
26.59. 
