<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Increase Bank Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government plans to
impose another round of bank capital increases after an ongoing
campaign is completed by end-2000, Journal newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu as saying a
further adjustment is necessary to further insulate the local
financial system from external shocks and give local banks more
muscle to compete on a regional scale.
</P>
<P>
Philippine banks at present observe a capital adequacy ratio of
10 percent, two percentage points higher than the internationally
observed level of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The capital adequacy ratio gauges capital strength in relation
to the so-called risk assets like loans and other credit
accommodations.
</P>
<P>
The higher the ratio the stronger the bank and those that fall
below the minimum must recapitalize, said Espiritu.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu pointed out that while present bank capital levels are
above the standards set by the Bank of International Settlements,
they are "still one of the lowest in the region in absolute
terms."
</P>
<P>
He said the combined capital of the three biggest banks in the
country "pale in comparison to Bangkok Bank or the Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi."
</P>
<P>
Under the schedule set by the Philippine Central Bank,
universal banks or banks with expanded licenses to engage in
non-bank allied areas must have 5.4-billion-peso
(135-million-U.S.-dollar) capital by end-2000.
</P>
<P>
Ordinary commercial banks must maintain 2.8 billion pesos (70
million dollars), thrift bank within Metro Manila at least 400
million pesos (10 million dollars) and thrift banks outside Metro
Manila at least 64 million pesos (1.6 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, Rafael Buenaventura, governor of the
central bank, has also acknowledged the possibility of imposing
another capital hike after the original schedule is completed.
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura said higher minimum capital would not only
encourage mergers and consolidations among local banks to face
stiffer competition but also enable the banks "to compete on a
regional basis." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Universities to Play Role in High-tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Education has
outlined a program to encourage colleges and universities to play
a greater role in economic growth, especially in the high-tech
sector, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quotes Wu Guilong, an
official from the Department of Science and Technology at the
ministry as saying that starting from next year, the state will
initiate "university-based high-tech projects" to bolster the
development of technologically advanced industries.
</P>
<P>
Through these projects, colleges and universities will
contribute more to developing key technologies for the country's
economic growth, upgrading traditional industries and speeding up
rural economic development.
</P>
<P>
The government has drawn up plans to stimulate knowledge
creation and technological innovation with the aim of speeding up
implementation of the strategy of "revitalizing the country
through science, technology and education", Wu said.
</P>
<P>
"A critical task for higher education institutions is to
nurture increasing numbers of specialized talents and to help
train highly skilled employees for enterprises," Wu said.
</P>
<P>
College teachers and students can operate high-tech enterprises
independently or set up industrialization centers around campuses.
</P>
<P>
Colleges and universities have become the backbone for
undertaking key national scientific projects and technology
upgrade programs for enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Each year, colleges and universities are responsible for about
70 percent of programs sponsored by national natural science funds
and 14 percent of state key projects, says the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba to Become Member of Latin American Integration Association </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, July 26 (Xinhua)-- Cuba will be a formal member of
the Latin American Integration Association within a month as Cuban
ambassador Miguel Martinez signed an official adhesion document at
the Uruguayan Foreign Ministry here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's full accession to the association, known by its Spanish
initials as Aladi, will be formalized 30 days after the signing.
</P>
<P>
Martinez also signed Aladi Regional Agreements as the country's
obligation. Cuba will enjoy the rights of relatively lesser
economically developed countries within Aladi.
</P>
<P>
Cuba submitted the application last March. The Ministerial
Council of Aladi approved the application last November. Cuba is
the first country admitted by this association after its
foundation in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Aladi is made up by Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Colombia, Chile,
Ecuador, Mexico, Paraguay, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
