<HEADLINE> China Fighting Pests to Save Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- China's forestry authorities and
workers are taking measures to control the outbreak of pine
nematode and gypsy moths, two dangerous types of pests ravaging
tress throughout China.
</P>
<P>
Vice-premier Wen Jiabao asked related departments to come up
with methods to prevent the epidemic from spreading any further,
today's China Daily says.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin city and Hebei, Shandong, Jiangsu, Zhejiang and Anhui
provinces have been affected by the pestilent plague.
</P>
<P>
Since last week, workers in those affected areas have been
working vigorously to control the epidemic, according to Li Yucai,
deputy director of the State Forestry Administration (SFA).
</P>
<P>
The government has spent a record 8 million yuan (963,855 U.S.
dollars) to prevent and control the two plant pests, SFA officials
confirmed yesterday.
