<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refugee Aid Disparity Draws International Attention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The disparity in aid to
refugees has been a focus of criticism at Monday's U.N. Security
Council meeting on humanitarian assistance to refugees.
</P>
<P>
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Sadako
Ogata said Kosovo and other emergencies attracted more attention
than other refugee programs.
</P>
<P>
The Serb province has been the focus of unprecedented
political attention and material support and in particular by
Western countries, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Undeniably, proximity, strategic interests and extraordinary
media focus have played a key role in determining the quality and
the level of response. However, that has not been true, and
continued not to be true, in other situations, including some of
those in Africa," she said.
</P>
<P>
During the council debate, Namibia's Martin Andjaba said the
level of financial and material assistance rendered to refugees in
other regions is far higher than what is available for Africa.
</P>
<P>
"I is unfortunate that selectivity is applied in providing
financial support," he said.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, out of 1.6 million U.S. dollars requested
through the appeal for Angola, only 14 percent has been made
available and of 27.9 million dollars for Sierra Leone, only 26
percent have reached the agencies.
</P>
<P>
Gelson Fonseca of Brazil said Brazil is sympathetic to
international calls for the same level of interest and political
involvement for the African refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Robert Fowler said the perception that Africa's
conflicts are neglected in favor of those in Europe must never be
allowed to take root or the very premise of the United Nations
would be called into question. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
