<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anelka Given Final Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- English Premier League club Arsenal
have given unsettled striker Nicolas Anelka until midday on
Tuesday to decide if he will take a massive pay cut to join
Italian club Lazio.
</P>
<P>
Lazio have agreed to pay 22 million pounds for the player in an
attempt to bring an end to the long running dispute over his
transfer.
</P>
<P>
The deal now depends on the Frenchman agreeing to take a cut in
wages - an incredible four million over five years - to move to
Italy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after Arsenal's 1-1 draw in a friendly against Monaco,
manager Arsene Wenger said: "We wait until tomorrow midday. If
there's no decision tomorrow morning then he has to come back (to
Arsenal)."
</P>
<P>
Lazio and Arsenal had previously failed to agree on a price for
Anelka with the Italians refusing to meet the 22m asking price.
</P>
<P>
Now the deal rests on Anelka agreeing to a lower salary package.
</P>
<P>
Anelka's agent, Marc Roget, said: "We have yet to reach an
agreement on Nicolas' personal terms, because Lazio have decided
they want to pay him four million less.
</P>
<P>
"But I am hopeful I can persuade Nicolas to accept the new
package and that a deal can be concluded."
</P>
<P>
Even if Anelka does agree to the salary cut, he will still earn
a reported 14 million over five years - 56,000 a week. Lazio have
also asked his agents to cut their fee.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Anelka's Arsenal team-mate and fellow Frenchman
Emmanuel Petit has criticised the 22m valuation.
</P>
<P>
"We are talking about too much money for just one player,"
Petit said.
</P>
<P>
"If Anelka does leave, then we'll probably need to buy another
striker very quickly - but I'm more concerned about the money
involved."
</P>
<P>
Petit believes Juventus striker Thierry Henry, who has been
strongly linked with the Gunners would be an excellent replacement
if Anelka does move to Italy.
</P>
<P>
"I know Henry very well and I think he would be a great player
for Arsenal.
</P>
<P>
"He could make a lot of difference for us," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
