<HEADLINE> Match-fixing Suspensions 'Overdue' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan cricket chief Mujeebur
Rehman has insisted the suspension of three of the country's top
players is long overdue, according to the BBC reports on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Captain Wasim Akram and batsmen Salim Malik and Ijaz Ahmed have
been removed from the national team pending investigations into
match-fixing charges.
</P>
<P>
Mujeebur, chairman of the ad hoc committee of the Pakistan
Cricket Board (PCB), said the three "will not be considered for
selection until the investigations are completed."
</P>
<P>
A PCB committee set up to investigate the matter and
recommended the players be suspended last year.
</P>
<P>
"I think the players should have been suspended there and then,
" Mujeebur said.
</P>
<P>
All three players have repeatedly denied any involvement in
match-fixing.
</P>
<P>
Wasim rejected the charges on British TV, saying: "I haven't
done anything wrong. I refute any charges, I always have done."
</P>
<P>
"The problem in Pakistan is that everybody gambles, rich guy,
poor guy, lawyer, they all gamble and when they lose they have to
blame someone so they blame the Pakistan team," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
