<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Press Highlights in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights of
major news items in leading Australian newspapers on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's Defense Department Secretary Paul Barratt has
taken the unprecedented move of calling in lawyers in an attempt
to stop his own minister, John Moore, from firing him.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- AMP, Australia's largest insurer, has returned to tradition
by appointing an internal candidate, Chief Financial Officer Paul
Batchelor, to replace its high-profile U.S.-born chief executive,
George Trumbull.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian government Monday promised fund managers who
bought shares in the initial float of Telstra, the country's
leading telecommunications company, that they would get favorable
treatment in the allocation of stock in the second tranche.
</P>
<P>
The Canberra Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Australians who contracted smoking-related diseases over the
past three years could win billions of Australian dollars in
damages in a landmark class action against the country's major
tobacco companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
