<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0040 GMT, July 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. National Association of Manufacturers (
NAM) Monday urged the House of Representatives to vote to maintain
normal trading relations with China by defeating Tuesday's
scheduled resolution of disapproval.
</P>
<P>
"Normal trading relation is not a favor we are doing for China,
it's a favor we are doing for ourselves," said Dianne Sullivan,
NAM director of trade policy. (US-China)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) Monday warned the international community of
another refugee crisis in Kosovo in the wake of increasing
incidents in the Serbian province recently.
</P>
<P>
The return of ethnic Albanians to Kosovo has coincided with the
expulsion, harassment and killing of people of non-Albanian
ethnicity, particularly Serbs and Romas, UNHCR Sadako Ogata told
the U.N. Security Council. (UN-Kosovo-Refugees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The euro hit two-month highs against the dollar
Monday, benefiting from broad dollar weakness and stronger-than-
expected consumer price data from North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany'
s largest state.
</P>
<P>
The single currency rose as high as 1.0722 U.S. dollars, its
strongest since mid-May and 5.7 percent higher than the life low
of 1.0104 U.S. dollars hit less than two weeks ago. (London-Euro-
Dollar)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Monday
hailed the arms destruction in Liberia as a welcome step and an
important confidence building gesture.
</P>
<P>
The move implies that the countries of the region are committed
to fighting the illegal proliferation of small arms, and to
implementing the arms moratoria adopted by the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOMOG), he said. (UN-Liberia-Weapons
Destruction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Foreign ministers from the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and the grouping's dialogue
partners Monday expressed the concern that the relations among the
major powers in the Asia-Pacific were affected by events in other
regions, including that in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers, attending a regional security forum in
Singapore, said that stable relations among the major powers were
an integral element underpinning regional stability. (ASEAN-Forum-
Statement) 
</P>
