<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stepashin Arrives in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin arrived in Washington Monday and is expected to meet
Vice President Al Gore and President Bill Clinton Tuesday to
repair U.S.-Russia relations strained over the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
They will talk about economic and security issues. "The focus
of the discussion will primarily be economics, as that is the
focus of Stepashin's portfolio," National Security Council
spokesman Mike Hammer said.
</P>
<P>
"Given Russia's return to discussions with NATO, the president
will certainly discuss post-Kosovo implementation and explore ways
to further cooperation with the Russians on winning the peace,"
Hammer added.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin arrived in Washington from Seattle two days before
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) board is due to approve a
new 4.5 billion U.S. dollar loan to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin's visit is the first by a Russian prime minister
since former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov turned back to Russia
on the way to the U.S. after being informed that NATO started
bombing Yugoslavia in March.
</P>
<P>
NATO's bombing has pushed the Russian-U.S. relationship to its
lowest point since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin's visit will be another effort to repair the ties
after Clinton and his Russian counterpart, Boris Yeltsin, met in
Germany during the G-8 summit last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
