<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Hits Two-Month High Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The euro hit two-month highs
against the dollar Monday, benefiting from broad dollar weakness
and stronger-than-expected consumer price data from North
Rhine-Westphalia, Germany's largest state.
</P>
<P>
The single currency rose as high as 1.0722 U.S. dollars, its
strongest since mid-May and 5.7 percent higher than the life low
of 1.0104 U.S. dollars hit less than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Demand for euros has been mounting in the past week amid
expectations that economic activity in Germany, Europe's largest
economy, is picking up.
</P>
<P>
Such talk was triggered after a stronger-than-expected rise was
reported last week in the Ifo economics institute's west German
business climate index. German state consumer price data has
further stoked such speculation.
</P>
<P>
Data released Monday showed consumer prices in Germany's
North-Rhine Westphalia rose by a larger-than-expected 0.5 percent
in July and were up 0.8 percent from a year earlier, according to
a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the dollar has suffered in recent days from losses
in the U.S. stocks and bonds amid concern that foreigners quitting
the U.S. asset market would sell dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency also fell as low as 1.5121 Swiss francs
Monday, its weakest since June 11, and eased to a one-month low
against the pound at 1.5882 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said there was room for the euro to rise to 1.0750 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Parity worries for euro/dollar are now over and we are
starting to get into new territory based on concerns about
generalized dollar weakness," Reuters quoted David Bloom, forex
strategist at HSBC Markets in London, as saying. "The big question
is: `Are currency markets adjusting to a new world order?'"
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Hails Arms Destruction in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday hailed the arms destruction in Liberia as a welcome
step and an important confidence building gesture.
</P>
<P>
The move implies that the countries of the region are committed
to fighting the illegal proliferation of small arms, and to
implementing the arms moratoria adopted by the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOMOG), he said.
</P>
<P>
"It signals that the peoples of the region will seek to settle
their disputes peacefully, through dialogue, and not through the
resort to arms," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the western African country's 152nd Independence Day which
fell on Monday, it held a ceremony to destroy arms and ammunition
collected by the United Nations and the Monitoring Group of the
ECOMOG at the end of a long time civil war in the country.
</P>
<P>
The burning of the weapons and ammunition began Sunday on the
Bomi hills near Tupmanburg, according to a U.N. spokesman.
</P>
<P>
A German non-governmental organization GTZ has been contracted
to manufacture farming implements out of the leftover metal,
spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
