<DOCNO> XIE19990727.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Prices Continue To Fall On Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks continued to
fall Monday amid fears of possibility of higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 47.80 at
10,863.16. The blue chip stocks fell 298.88 points or 2.7 percent
last week.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index fell 73.21 at 2,619.19 and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 9.18 at 1,347.76.
</P>
<P>
The market plunged as investors were nervous about higher
interest rates after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
raised the possibility in the testimony at the House Banking
Committee last Thursday. Greenspan will address a Senate panel
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan said the Federal Reserve must be "especially alert"
to inflation risks and be prepared to "act promptly and
forcefully" to avoid the need for more rate hikes later.
</P>
<P>
Among the companies hit the hardest were Microsoft and America
Online. Microsoft fell steeply and America Online lost ground as
its several top executives including Chairman and Chief Executive
Stephen Case sold 4 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 2.97 at 635.90 and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 5.50 at 790.79. the Russell
2000 index of smaller companies fell 5.51 at 442.87.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,051 down, 969 up and 511
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 611.18 million shares from 628.94
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
