<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Will Urged to Solve Refugee Problem in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Monday appealed to African
governments to renew their commitments to resolve the refugee
problem through negotiations instead of force.
</P>
<P>
"This is a fundamental precondition for international support,"
UNHCR Sadako Ogata told the Security Council which met on
promoting peace and security: humanitarian assistance to refugees
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
She called for resources from the international community to
support the implementation of the Sierra Leone peace agreement and
the Lusaka agreement to cease fire in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) as the accords could help resolve some of the
worst refugee problems in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Sadako Ogata said her office spends over 40 percent of its
resources in Africa which has about 6 million people of concern to
her office, including refugees and displaced persons as a result
of conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Recent crises have added the number of the people "of concern,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Such people include over half a million Sierra Leoneans, the
260,000 Burundians and 150,000 people who have fled conflict in
the DRC, she said.
</P>
<P>
There are older, unresolved conflict situations which have
produced refugees many years ago, she added.
</P>
<P>
More than 370,000 Sundanese continue to be refugees in Uganda
and Ethiopia, and 120,000 Saharan refugees are still in camps in
Algeria and other countries, plus 150,000 Angolan refugees
elsewhere, she noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
